02421 /**
02422  * cvmx_bgx#_cmr#_config
02423  *
02424  * Logical MAC/PCS configuration registers; one per LMAC. The maximum number of LMACs (and
02425  * maximum LMAC ID) that can be enabled by these registers is limited by
02426  * BGX()_CMR_RX_LMACS[LMACS] and BGX()_CMR_TX_LMACS[LMACS]. When multiple LMACs are
02427  * enabled, they must be configured with the same [LMAC_TYPE] value.
02428  */
02429 union cvmx_bgxx_cmrx_config {
02430     uint64_t u64;
02431     struct cvmx_bgxx_cmrx_config_s {
02432 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
02433     uint64_t reserved_16_63               : 48;
02434     uint64_t enable                       : 1;  /**< Logical MAC/PCS enable. This is the master enable for the LMAC. When clear, all the
02435                                                          dedicated BGX context state for the LMAC (state machines, FIFOs, counters, etc.) is reset,
02436                                                          and LMAC access to shared BGX resources (SMU/SPU data path, SerDes lanes) is disabled.
02437                                                          When set, LMAC operation is enabled, including link bring-up, synchronization, and
02438                                                          transmit/receive of idles and fault sequences. Note that configuration registers for an
02439                                                          LMAC are not reset when this bit is clear, allowing software to program them before
02440                                                          setting this bit to enable the LMAC. This bit together with [LMAC_TYPE] is also used to
02441                                                          enable the clocking to the GMP and/or blocks of the Super path (SMU and SPU). CMR clocking
02442                                                          is enabled when any of the paths are enabled. */
02443     uint64_t data_pkt_rx_en               : 1;  /**< Data packet receive enable. When [ENABLE] = 1 and [DATA_PKT_RX_EN] = 1, the reception of
02444                                                          data
02445                                                          packets is enabled in the MAC layer. When [ENABLE] = 1 and [DATA_PKT_RX_EN] = 0, the MAC
02446                                                          layer
02447                                                          drops received data and flow-control packets. */
02448     uint64_t data_pkt_tx_en               : 1;  /**< Data packet transmit enable. When [ENABLE] = 1 and [DATA_PKT_TX_EN] = 1, the transmission
02449                                                          of
02450                                                          data
02451                                                          packets is enabled in the MAC layer. When [ENABLE] = 1 and [DATA_PKT_TX_EN] = 0, the MAC
02452                                                          layer
02453                                                          suppresses the transmission of new data and packets for the LMAC. */
02454     uint64_t int_beat_gen                 : 1;  /**< Internal beat generation. This bit is used for debug/test purposes and should be clear
02455                                                          during normal operation. When set, the LMAC's PCS layer ignores RXVALID and
02456                                                          TXREADY/TXCREDIT from the associated SerDes lanes, internally generates fake (idle)
02457                                                          RXVALID and TXCREDIT pulses, and suppresses transmission to the SerDes. */
02458     uint64_t mix_en                       : 1;  /**< Management enable. This bit is used by LMACs 0 and 1 only, and should be kept clear for
02459                                                          LMACs 2 and 3. Setting it will pipe the LMAC to and from the MIX interface (LMAC0 to/from
02460                                                          MIX0, LMAC1 to/from MIX1).  [LMAC_TYPE] must be 0 (SGMII) then this bit is set.
02461                                                          This field must be programmed to its final value before [ENABLE] is set, and must not
02462                                                          be changed when [ENABLE]=1. */
02463     uint64_t lmac_type                    : 3;  /**< Logical MAC/PCS/prt type:
02464                                                          <pre>
02465                                                            LMAC_TYPE  Name       Description            NUM_PCS_LANES
02466                                                            ----------------------------------------------------------
02467                                                            0x0        SGMII      SGMII/1000BASE-X             1
02468                                                            0x1        XAUI       10GBASE-X/XAUI or DXAUI      4
02469                                                            0x2        RXAUI      Reduced XAUI                 2
02470                                                            0x3        10G_R      10GBASE-R                    1
02471                                                            0x4        40G_R      40GBASE-R                    4
02472                                                            0x5        RGMII      RGMII                        -
02473                                                            Other      --         Reserved                     -
02474                                                          </pre>
02475                                                          NUM_PCS_LANES specifies the number of PCS lanes that are valid for
02476                                                          each type. Each valid PCS lane is mapped to a physical SerDes lane
02477                                                          based on the programming of [LANE_TO_SDS].
02478                                                          In the case of RGMII, the XCV interface is used instead of the PCS lane and
02479                                                          SerDes interface.  The RGMII setting is only available for LMAC 0.
02480                                                          This field must be programmed to its final value before [ENABLE] is set, and must not
02481                                                          be changed when [ENABLE] = 1. */
02482     uint64_t lane_to_sds                  : 8;  /**< PCS lane-to-SerDes mapping.
02483                                                          This is an array of 2-bit values that map each logical PCS lane to a
02484                                                          physical SerDes lane, as follows:
02485                                                          <pre>
02486                                                            Bits    Description            Reset value
02487                                                            ------------------------------------------
02488                                                            <7:6>   PCS Lane 3 SerDes ID       0x3
02489                                                            <5:4>   PCS Lane 2 SerDes ID       0x2
02490                                                            <3:2>   PCS Lane 1 SerDes ID       0x1
02491                                                            <1:0>   PCS Lane 0 SerDes ID       0x0
02492                                                          </pre>
02493                                                          PCS lanes 0 through NUM_PCS_LANES-1 are valid, where NUM_PCS_LANES is a function of the
02494                                                          logical MAC/PCS type (see [LMAC_TYPE]). For example, when [LMAC_TYPE] = RXAUI,
02495                                                          then NUM_PCS_LANES = 2, PCS lanes 0 and 1 valid and the associated physical SerDes lanes
02496                                                          are selected by bits <1:0> and <3:2>, respectively.
02497                                                          For 40GBASE-R ([LMAC_TYPE] = 40G_R), all four PCS lanes are valid, and the PCS lane IDs
02498                                                          determine the block distribution order and associated alignment markers on the transmit
02499                                                          side. This is not necessarily the order in which PCS lanes receive data because 802.3
02500                                                          allows multilane BASE-R receive lanes to be reordered. When a lane (called service
02501                                                          interface in 802.3ba-2010) has achieved alignment marker lock on the receive side (i.e.
02502                                                          the associated BGX()_SPU()_BR_ALGN_STATUS[MARKER_LOCK] = 1), then the actual
02503                                                          detected RX PCS lane number is recorded in the corresponding
02504                                                          BGX()_SPU()_BR_LANE_MAP[LNx_MAPPING].
02505                                                          This field must be programmed to its final value before [ENABLE] is set, and must not
02506                                                          be changed when [ENABLE] = 1. */
02507 #else
02508     uint64_t lane_to_sds                  : 8;
02509     uint64_t lmac_type                    : 3;
02510     uint64_t mix_en                       : 1;
02511     uint64_t int_beat_gen                 : 1;
02512     uint64_t data_pkt_tx_en               : 1;
02513     uint64_t data_pkt_rx_en               : 1;
02514     uint64_t enable                       : 1;
02515     uint64_t reserved_16_63               : 48;
02516 #endif
02517     } s;
02518     struct cvmx_bgxx_cmrx_config_s        cn73xx;
02519     struct cvmx_bgxx_cmrx_config_s        cn78xx;
02520     struct cvmx_bgxx_cmrx_config_s        cn78xxp1;
02521     struct cvmx_bgxx_cmrx_config_s        cnf75xx;
02522 };
02523 typedef union cvmx_bgxx_cmrx_config cvmx_bgxx_cmrx_config_t;
02524 
02525 /**
02526  * cvmx_bgx#_cmr#_int
02527  */
02528 union cvmx_bgxx_cmrx_int {
02529     uint64_t u64;
02530     struct cvmx_bgxx_cmrx_int_s {
02531 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
02532     uint64_t reserved_3_63                : 61;
02533     uint64_t pko_nxc                      : 1;  /**< TX channel out-of-range from PKO interface. */
02534     uint64_t overflw                      : 1;  /**< RX overflow. */
02535     uint64_t pause_drp                    : 1;  /**< RX PAUSE packet was dropped due to full RXB FIFO or during partner reset. */
02536 #else
02537     uint64_t pause_drp                    : 1;
02538     uint64_t overflw                      : 1;
02539     uint64_t pko_nxc                      : 1;
02540     uint64_t reserved_3_63                : 61;
02541 #endif
02542     } s;
02543     struct cvmx_bgxx_cmrx_int_s           cn73xx;
02544     struct cvmx_bgxx_cmrx_int_s           cn78xx;
02545     struct cvmx_bgxx_cmrx_int_s           cn78xxp1;
02546     struct cvmx_bgxx_cmrx_int_s           cnf75xx;
02547 };
02548 typedef union cvmx_bgxx_cmrx_int cvmx_bgxx_cmrx_int_t;

02550 /**
02551  * cvmx_bgx#_cmr#_prt_cbfc_ctl
02552  *
02553  * See XOFF definition listed under BGX()_SMU()_CBFC_CTL.
02554  *
02555  */
02556 union cvmx_bgxx_cmrx_prt_cbfc_ctl {
02557     uint64_t u64;
02558     struct cvmx_bgxx_cmrx_prt_cbfc_ctl_s {
02559 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
02560     uint64_t reserved_32_63               : 32;
02561     uint64_t phys_bp                      : 16; /**< When BGX()_SMU()_CBFC_CTL[RX_EN] is set and the hardware is backpressuring any
02562                                                          LMACs (from either PFC packets or BGX()_CMR()_TX_OVR_BP[TX_CHAN_BP])
02563                                                          and all LMACs indicated by [PHYS_BP] are backpressured, simulate physical backpressure by
02564                                                          deferring all packets on the transmitter. */
02565     uint64_t reserved_0_15                : 16;
02566 #else
02567     uint64_t reserved_0_15                : 16;
02568     uint64_t phys_bp                      : 16;
02569     uint64_t reserved_32_63               : 32;
02570 #endif
02571     } s;
02572     struct cvmx_bgxx_cmrx_prt_cbfc_ctl_s  cn73xx;
02573     struct cvmx_bgxx_cmrx_prt_cbfc_ctl_s  cn78xx;

02666     uint64_t reserved_12_63               : 52;
02667     uint64_t mark                         : 12; /**< High watermark. Buffer depth in multiple of 16-bytes, at which BGX will
02668                                                          assert backpressure for each individual LMAC. Must satisfy:
02669                                                            BGX()_CMR()_RX_BP_OFF[MARK] <= BGX()_CMR()_RX_BP_ON[MARK] <
02670                                                            (FIFO_SIZE - BGX()_CMR()_RX_BP_DROP[MARK]).
02671                                                          A value of 0x0 immediately asserts backpressure.
02672                                                          The recommended value is 1/4th the size of the per-LMAC RX FIFO_SIZE as
02673                                                          determined by BGX()_CMR_RX_LMACS[LMACS]. For example in SGMII mode with
02674                                                          four LMACs of type SGMII, where BGX()_CMR_RX_LMACS[LMACS]=0x4, there is
02675                                                          16 KB of buffering. The recommended 1/4th size of that 16 KB is 4 KB, which
02676                                                          in units of 16 bytes gives [MARK] = 0x100 (the reset value). */
02677 #else

02679     uint64_t reserved_12_63               : 52;
02680 #endif
02681     } s;

03014  *
03015  * These registers provide a count of all packets received that were dropped due to a full
03016  * receive FIFO. They do not count any packet that is truncated at the point of overflow and sent
03017  * on to the PKI. These registers count all entire packets dropped by the FIFO for a given LMAC
03018  * regardless of DMAC or PAUSE type.
03019  */
03020 union cvmx_bgxx_cmrx_rx_stat6 {
03021     uint64_t u64;
03022     struct cvmx_bgxx_cmrx_rx_stat6_s {
03023 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
03024     uint64_t reserved_48_63               : 16;
03025     uint64_t cnt                          : 48; /**< Count of dropped packets. [CNT] will wrap and is cleared if LMAC is disabled with
03026                                                          BGX()_CMR()_CONFIG[ENABLE]=0. */
03027 #else
03028     uint64_t cnt                          : 48;
03029     uint64_t reserved_48_63               : 16;
03030 #endif
03031     } s;
03032     struct cvmx_bgxx_cmrx_rx_stat6_s      cn73xx;
03033     struct cvmx_bgxx_cmrx_rx_stat6_s      cn78xx;
03034     struct cvmx_bgxx_cmrx_rx_stat6_s      cn78xxp1;
03035     struct cvmx_bgxx_cmrx_rx_stat6_s      cnf75xx;
03036 };
03037 typedef union cvmx_bgxx_cmrx_rx_stat6 cvmx_bgxx_cmrx_rx_stat6_t;

03064 /**
03065  * cvmx_bgx#_cmr#_rx_stat8
03066  *
03067  * These registers provide a count of all packets received with some error that were not dropped
03068  * either due to the DMAC filter or lack of room in the receive FIFO.
03069  * This does not include packets which were counted in
03070  * BGX()_CMR()_RX_STAT2, BGX()_CMR()_RX_STAT4 nor
03071  * BGX()_CMR()_RX_STAT6.
03072  *
03073  * Which statistics are updated on control packet errors and drops are shown below:
03074  *
03075  * <pre>
03076  * if dropped [
03077  *   if !errored STAT8
03078  *   if overflow STAT6
03079  *   else if dmac drop STAT4
03080  *   else if filter drop STAT2
03081  * ] else [
03082  *   if errored STAT2
03083  *   else STAT8
03084  * ]
03085  * </pre>
03086  */
03087 union cvmx_bgxx_cmrx_rx_stat8 {
03088     uint64_t u64;
03089     struct cvmx_bgxx_cmrx_rx_stat8_s {
03090 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
03091     uint64_t reserved_48_63               : 16;
03092     uint64_t cnt                          : 48; /**< Count of error packets. [CNT] will wrap and is cleared if LMAC is disabled with
03093                                                          BGX()_CMR()_CONFIG[ENABLE]=0. */
03094 #else
03095     uint64_t cnt                          : 48;
03096     uint64_t reserved_48_63               : 16;
03097 #endif
03098     } s;
03099     struct cvmx_bgxx_cmrx_rx_stat8_s      cn73xx;
03100     struct cvmx_bgxx_cmrx_rx_stat8_s      cn78xx;
03101     struct cvmx_bgxx_cmrx_rx_stat8_s      cn78xxp1;
03102     struct cvmx_bgxx_cmrx_rx_stat8_s      cnf75xx;
03103 };
03104 typedef union cvmx_bgxx_cmrx_rx_stat8 cvmx_bgxx_cmrx_rx_stat8_t;

03807 /**
03808  * cvmx_bgx#_cmr_global_config
03809  *
03810  * These registers configure the global CMR, PCS, and MAC.
03811  *
03812  */
03813 union cvmx_bgxx_cmr_global_config {
03814     uint64_t u64;
03815     struct cvmx_bgxx_cmr_global_config_s {
03816 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
03817     uint64_t reserved_5_63                : 59;
03818     uint64_t cmr_mix1_reset               : 1;  /**< If the MIX1 block is reset, software also needs to reset the MIX interface in the BGX by
03819                                                          setting this bit to 1. It resets the MIX interface state in the BGX (mix FIFO and pending
03820                                                          requests to MIX) and prevents the RXB FIFOs for all LMACs from pushing data to the
03821                                                          interface. Setting this bit to 0 will not reset the MIX interface. After MIX comes out of
03822                                                          reset, software should clear this bit. */
03823     uint64_t cmr_mix0_reset               : 1;  /**< If the MIX0 block is reset, software also needs to reset the MIX interface in the BGX by
03824                                                          setting this bit to 1. It resets the MIX interface state in the BGX (mix FIFO and pending
03825                                                          requests to MIX) and prevents the RXB FIFOs for all LMACs from pushing data to the
03826                                                          interface. Setting this bit to 0 will not reset the MIX interface. After MIX comes out of
03827                                                          reset, software should clear this bit. */
03828     uint64_t cmr_x2p_reset                : 1;  /**< If the PKI block is reset, software also needs to reset the X2P interface in the BGX by
03829                                                          setting this bit to 1. It resets the X2P interface state in the BGX (skid FIFO and pending
03830                                                          requests to PKI) and prevents the RXB FIFOs for all LMACs from pushing data to the
03831                                                          interface. Setting this bit to 0 does not reset the X2P interface. After PKI comes out of
03832                                                          reset, software should clear this bit. */
03833     uint64_t bgx_clk_enable               : 1;  /**< The global clock enable for BGX. Setting this bit overrides clock enables set by
03834                                                          BGX()_CMR()_CONFIG[ENABLE] and BGX()_CMR()_CONFIG[LMAC_TYPE], essentially
03835                                                          turning on clocks for the entire BGX. Setting this bit to 0 results in not overriding
03836                                                          clock enables set by BGX()_CMR()_CONFIG[ENABLE] and
03837                                                          BGX()_CMR()_CONFIG[LMAC_TYPE]. */
03838     uint64_t pmux_sds_sel                 : 1;  /**< SerDes/QLM output select. Must be 0. */
03839 #else
03840     uint64_t pmux_sds_sel                 : 1;
03841     uint64_t bgx_clk_enable               : 1;
03842     uint64_t cmr_x2p_reset                : 1;
03843     uint64_t cmr_mix0_reset               : 1;
03844     uint64_t cmr_mix1_reset               : 1;
03845     uint64_t reserved_5_63                : 59;
03846 #endif
03847     } s;
03848     struct cvmx_bgxx_cmr_global_config_s  cn73xx;
03849     struct cvmx_bgxx_cmr_global_config_s  cn78xx;
03850     struct cvmx_bgxx_cmr_global_config_s  cn78xxp1;

03858 union cvmx_bgxx_cmr_mem_ctrl {

03861 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
03862     uint64_t reserved_24_63               : 40;
03863     uint64_t txb_skid_synd                : 2;  /**< Syndrome to flip and generate single-bit/double-bit for TXB SKID FIFO. */
03864     uint64_t txb_skid_cor_dis             : 1;  /**< ECC-correction disable for the TXB SKID FIFO. */
03865     uint64_t txb_fif_bk1_syn              : 2;  /**< Syndrome to flip and generate single-bit/double-bit error for TXB main bank1. */
03866     uint64_t txb_fif_bk1_cdis             : 1;  /**< ECC-correction disable for the TXB main bank1. */
03867     uint64_t txb_fif_bk0_syn              : 2;  /**< Syndrome to flip and generate single-bit/double-bit error for TXB main bank0. */

03869     uint64_t rxb_skid_synd                : 2;  /**< Syndrome to flip and generate single-bit/double-bit error for RXB SKID FIFO. */

03984 /**
03985  * cvmx_bgx#_cmr_rx_adr#_cam
03986  *
03987  * These registers provide access to the 32 DMAC CAM entries in BGX.
03988  *
03989  */
03990 union cvmx_bgxx_cmr_rx_adrx_cam {
03991     uint64_t u64;
03992     struct cvmx_bgxx_cmr_rx_adrx_cam_s {
03993 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
03994     uint64_t reserved_54_63               : 10;
03995     uint64_t id                           : 2;  /**< Logical MAC ID that this DMAC CAM address applies to. BGX has 32 DMAC CAM entries that can
03996                                                          be accessed with these registers. These 32 DMAC entries can be used by
03997                                                          any of the four SGMII MACs or the 10G/40G MACs using these register bits.
03998                                                          A typical configuration is to provide eight CAM entries per LMAC ID, which is configured
03999                                                          using the following settings:
04000                                                          * LMAC interface 0: BGX()_CMR_RX_ADR(0..7)_CAM[ID] = 0x0.
04001                                                          * LMAC interface 1: BGX()_CMR_RX_ADR(8..15)_CAM[ID] = 0x1.
04002                                                          * LMAC interface 2: BGX()_CMR_RX_ADR(16..23)_CAM[ID] = 0x2.
04003                                                          * LMAC interface 3: BGX()_CMR_RX_ADR(24..31)_CAM[ID] = 0x3. */
04004     uint64_t reserved_49_51               : 3;
04005     uint64_t en                           : 1;  /**< CAM entry enable for this DMAC address.
04006                                                          1 = Include this address in the matching algorithm.
04007                                                          0 = Don't include this address in the matching algorithm. */
04008     uint64_t adr                          : 48; /**< DMAC address in the CAM used for matching. Specified in network byte order, i.e.
04009                                                          ADR<47:40> is for the first DMAC byte on the wire. The CAM matches against unicast or
04010                                                          multicast DMAC addresses. All BGX()_CMR_RX_ADR()_CAM CSRs can be used in any of the LMAC
04011                                                          combinations such that any BGX MAC can use any of the 32 common DMAC entries. */
04012 #else
04013     uint64_t adr                          : 48;
04014     uint64_t en                           : 1;
04015     uint64_t reserved_49_51               : 3;
04016     uint64_t id                           : 2;
04017     uint64_t reserved_54_63               : 10;
04018 #endif
04019     } s;
04020     struct cvmx_bgxx_cmr_rx_adrx_cam_s    cn73xx;
04021     struct cvmx_bgxx_cmr_rx_adrx_cam_s    cn78xx;
04022     struct cvmx_bgxx_cmr_rx_adrx_cam_s    cn78xxp1;
04023     struct cvmx_bgxx_cmr_rx_adrx_cam_s    cnf75xx;

04248  *
04249  * This register controls the handling of the frames.
04250  * The [CTL_BCK] and [CTL_DRP] bits control how the hardware handles incoming PAUSE packets. The
04251  * most
04252  * common modes of operation:
04253  * _ [CTL_BCK] = 1, [CTL_DRP] = 1: hardware handles everything.
04254  * _ [CTL_BCK] = 0, [CTL_DRP] = 0: software sees all PAUSE frames.
04255  * _ [CTL_BCK] = 0, [CTL_DRP] = 1: all PAUSE frames are completely ignored.
04256  *
04257  * These control bits should be set to [CTL_BCK] = 0, [CTL_DRP] = 0 in half-duplex mode. Since
04258  * PAUSE
04259  * packets only apply to full duplex operation, any PAUSE packet would constitute an exception
04260  * which should be handled by the processing cores. PAUSE packets should not be forwarded.
04261  */
04262 union cvmx_bgxx_gmp_gmi_rxx_frm_ctl {
04263     uint64_t u64;
04264     struct cvmx_bgxx_gmp_gmi_rxx_frm_ctl_s {
04265 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
04266     uint64_t reserved_13_63               : 51;
04267     uint64_t ptp_mode                     : 1;  /**< Timestamp mode. When [PTP_MODE] is set, a 64-bit timestamp is prepended to every incoming
04268                                                          packet.
04269                                                          The timestamp bytes are added to the packet in such a way as to not modify the packet's
04270                                                          receive byte count. This implies that the BGX()_GMP_GMI_RX()_JABBER,
04271                                                          BGX()_GMP_GMI_RX()_DECISION, BGX()_GMP_GMI_RX()_UDD_SKP, and
04272                                                          BGX()_CMR()_RX_STAT0..BGX()_CMR()_RX_STAT8
04273                                                          do not require any adjustment as they operate on the received
04274                                                          packet size. When the packet reaches PKI, its size reflects the additional bytes and is
04275                                                          subject to the following restrictions:
04276                                                          If [PTP_MODE] = 1 and [PRE_CHK] = 1, [PRE_STRP] must be 1.
04277                                                          If [PTP_MODE] = 1:
04278                                                          * PKI_CL()_PKIND()_SKIP[FCS_SKIP,INST_SKIP] should be increased by 8.
04279                                                          * PKI_CL()_PKIND()_CFG[HG_EN] should be 0.
04280                                                          * PKI_FRM_LEN_CHK()[MAXLEN] should be increased by 8.
04281                                                          * PKI_FRM_LEN_CHK()[MINLEN] should be increased by 8.
04282                                                          * PKI_TAG_INC()_MASK[EN] should be adjusted. */
04283     uint64_t reserved_11_11               : 1;
04284     uint64_t null_dis                     : 1;  /**< When set, do not modify the MOD bits on NULL ticks due to partial packets. */
04285     uint64_t pre_align                    : 1;  /**< When set, PREAMBLE parser aligns the SFD byte regardless of the number of previous
04286                                                          PREAMBLE nibbles. In this mode, [PRE_STRP] should be set to account for the variable
04287                                                          nature of the PREAMBLE. [PRE_CHK] must be set to enable this and all PREAMBLE features.
04288                                                          SGMII at 10/100Mbs only. */
04289     uint64_t reserved_7_8                 : 2;
04290     uint64_t pre_free                     : 1;  /**< When set, PREAMBLE checking is less strict. GMI will begin the frame at the first SFD.
04291                                                          [PRE_CHK] must be set to enable this and all PREAMBLE features. SGMII/1000Base-X only. */
04292     uint64_t ctl_smac                     : 1;  /**< Control PAUSE frames can match station SMAC. */
04293     uint64_t ctl_mcst                     : 1;  /**< Control PAUSE frames can match globally assigned multicast address. */
04294     uint64_t ctl_bck                      : 1;  /**< Forward PAUSE information to TX block. */
04295     uint64_t ctl_drp                      : 1;  /**< Drop control-PAUSE frames. */
04296     uint64_t pre_strp                     : 1;  /**< Strip off the preamble (when present).
04297                                                          0 = PREAMBLE + SFD is sent to core as part of frame.
04298                                                          1 = PREAMBLE + SFD is dropped.
04299                                                          [PRE_CHK] must be set to enable this and all PREAMBLE features.
04300                                                          If [PTP_MODE]=1 and [PRE_CHK]=1, [PRE_STRP] must be 1.
04301                                                          When [PRE_CHK] is set (indicating that the PREAMBLE will be sent), [PRE_STRP] determines
04302                                                          if
04303                                                          the PREAMBLE+SFD bytes are thrown away or sent to the core as part of the packet. In
04304                                                          either mode, the PREAMBLE+SFD bytes are not counted toward the packet size when checking
04305                                                          against the MIN and MAX bounds. Furthermore, the bytes are skipped when locating the start
04306                                                          of the L2 header for DMAC and control frame recognition. */
04307     uint64_t pre_chk                      : 1;  /**< Check the preamble for correctness. This port is configured to send a valid 802.3 PREAMBLE
04308                                                          to begin every frame. GMI checks that a valid PREAMBLE is received (based on [PRE_FREE]).
04309                                                          When a problem does occur within the PREAMBLE sequence, the frame is marked as bad and not
04310                                                          sent into the core. The BGX()_SMU()_RX_INT[PCTERR] interrupt is also raised.
04311                                                          When BGX()_SMU()_TX_CTL[HG_EN] is set, [PRE_CHK] must be 0. If [PTP_MODE] = 1 and
04312                                                          [PRE_CHK] = 1, [PRE_STRP] must be 1. */
04313 #else
04314     uint64_t pre_chk                      : 1;
04315     uint64_t pre_strp                     : 1;
04316     uint64_t ctl_drp                      : 1;
04317     uint64_t ctl_bck                      : 1;
04318     uint64_t ctl_mcst                     : 1;
04319     uint64_t ctl_smac                     : 1;
04320     uint64_t pre_free                     : 1;
04321     uint64_t reserved_7_8                 : 2;
04322     uint64_t pre_align                    : 1;
04323     uint64_t null_dis                     : 1;
04324     uint64_t reserved_11_11               : 1;
04325     uint64_t ptp_mode                     : 1;
04326     uint64_t reserved_13_63               : 51;
04327 #endif
04328     } s;
04329     struct cvmx_bgxx_gmp_gmi_rxx_frm_ctl_s cn73xx;
04330     struct cvmx_bgxx_gmp_gmi_rxx_frm_ctl_s cn78xx;
04331     struct cvmx_bgxx_gmp_gmi_rxx_frm_ctl_s cn78xxp1;
04332     struct cvmx_bgxx_gmp_gmi_rxx_frm_ctl_s cnf75xx;
04333 };
04334 typedef union cvmx_bgxx_gmp_gmi_rxx_frm_ctl cvmx_bgxx_gmp_gmi_rxx_frm_ctl_t;

04348                                                          bits. Values 0x1 or smaller are illegal.

04365 /**
04366  * cvmx_bgx#_gmp_gmi_rx#_int
04367  *
04368  * '"These registers allow interrupts to be sent to the control processor.
04369  * * Exception conditions <10:0> can also set the rcv/opcode in the received packet's work-queue
04370  * entry. BGX()_GMP_GMI_RX()_FRM_CHK provides a bit mask for configuring which conditions
04371  * set the error.
04372  * In half duplex operation, the expectation is that collisions will appear as either MINERR or
04373  * CAREXT errors.'
04374  */
04375 union cvmx_bgxx_gmp_gmi_rxx_int {
04376     uint64_t u64;
04377     struct cvmx_bgxx_gmp_gmi_rxx_int_s {
04378 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
04379     uint64_t reserved_12_63               : 52;
04380     uint64_t ifgerr                       : 1;  /**< Interframe gap violation. Does not necessarily indicate a failure. SGMII/1000Base-X only. */
04381     uint64_t coldet                       : 1;  /**< Collision detection. Collisions can only occur in half-duplex mode. A collision is assumed
04382                                                          by the receiver when the slottime (BGX()_GMP_GMI_PRT()_CFG[SLOTTIME]) is not
04383                                                          satisfied. In 10/100 mode, this will result in a frame < SLOTTIME. In 1000 mode, it could
04384                                                          result either in frame < SLOTTIME or a carrier extend error with the SLOTTIME. These
04385                                                          conditions are visible by 1) transfer ended before slottime - COLDET or 2) carrier extend
04386                                                          error - CAREXT. */
04387     uint64_t falerr                       : 1;  /**< False-carrier error, or carrier-extend error after slottime is satisfied. SGMII/1000Base-X only. */
04388     uint64_t rsverr                       : 1;  /**< Reserved opcode. */
04389     uint64_t pcterr                       : 1;  /**< Bad preamble/protocol error. Checks that the frame begins with a valid PREAMBLE sequence.
04390                                                          Does not check the number of PREAMBLE cycles. */
04391     uint64_t ovrerr                       : 1;  /**< Internal data aggregation overflow. This interrupt should never assert. SGMII/1000Base-X only. */
04392     uint64_t skperr                       : 1;  /**< Skipper error. */
04393     uint64_t rcverr                       : 1;  /**< Data-reception error. Frame was received with data-reception error. */
04394     uint64_t fcserr                       : 1;  /**< FCS/CRC error. Frame was received with FCS/CRC error. */
04395     uint64_t jabber                       : 1;  /**< System-length error: frame was received with length > sys_length.
04396                                                          An RX Jabber error indicates that a packet was received which is longer than the maximum
04397                                                          allowed packet as defined by the system. GMI truncates the packet at the JABBER count.
04398                                                          Failure to do so could lead to system instability. */
04399     uint64_t carext                       : 1;  /**< Carrier-extend error. (SGMII/1000Base-X only) */
04400     uint64_t minerr                       : 1;  /**< PAUSE frame was received with length < minFrameSize. Frame length checks are typically
04401                                                          handled in PKI, but PAUSE frames are normally discarded before being inspected by PKI.
04402                                                          Total frame DA+SA+TL+DATA+PAD+FCS < 64. */
04403 #else
04404     uint64_t minerr                       : 1;
04405     uint64_t carext                       : 1;
04406     uint64_t jabber                       : 1;
04407     uint64_t fcserr                       : 1;
04408     uint64_t rcverr                       : 1;
04409     uint64_t skperr                       : 1;
04410     uint64_t ovrerr                       : 1;
04411     uint64_t pcterr                       : 1;
04412     uint64_t rsverr                       : 1;
04413     uint64_t falerr                       : 1;
04414     uint64_t coldet                       : 1;
04415     uint64_t ifgerr                       : 1;
04416     uint64_t reserved_12_63               : 52;
04417 #endif
04418     } s;
04419     struct cvmx_bgxx_gmp_gmi_rxx_int_s    cn73xx;
04420     struct cvmx_bgxx_gmp_gmi_rxx_int_s    cn78xx;
04421     struct cvmx_bgxx_gmp_gmi_rxx_int_s    cn78xxp1;

04857 /**
04858  * cvmx_bgx#_gmp_gmi_tx_ifg
04859  *
04860  * Consider the following when programming IFG1 and IFG2:
04861  * * For 10/100/1000 Mb/s half-duplex systems that require IEEE 802.3 compatibility, IFG1 must be
04862  * in the range of 1-8, IFG2 must be in the range of 4-12, and the IFG1 + IFG2 sum must be 12.
04863  * * For 10/100/1000 Mb/s full-duplex systems that require IEEE 802.3 compatibility, IFG1 must be
04864  * in the range of 1-11, IFG2 must be in the range of 1-11, and the IFG1 + IFG2 sum must be 12.
04865  * For all other systems, IFG1 and IFG2 can be any value in the range of 1-15, allowing for a
04866  * total possible IFG sum of 2-30.
04867  */
04868 union cvmx_bgxx_gmp_gmi_tx_ifg {
04869     uint64_t u64;
04870     struct cvmx_bgxx_gmp_gmi_tx_ifg_s {
04871 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
04872     uint64_t reserved_8_63                : 56;
04873     uint64_t ifg2                         : 4;  /**< Remainder of interFrameGap timing, equal to interFrameGap - IFG1 (in IFG2 * 8 bits). If
04874                                                          CRS is detected during IFG2, the interFrameSpacing timer is not reset and a frame is
04875                                                          transmitted once the timer expires. */
04876     uint64_t ifg1                         : 4;  /**< First portion of interFrameGap timing, in the range of 0 to 2/3 (in IFG2 * 8 bits). If CRS
04877                                                          is detected during IFG1, the interFrameSpacing timer is reset and a frame is not
04878                                                          transmitted. */
04879 #else
04880     uint64_t ifg1                         : 4;
04881     uint64_t ifg2                         : 4;
04882     uint64_t reserved_8_63                : 56;
04883 #endif
04884     } s;
04885     struct cvmx_bgxx_gmp_gmi_tx_ifg_s     cn73xx;
04886     struct cvmx_bgxx_gmp_gmi_tx_ifg_s     cn78xx;
04887     struct cvmx_bgxx_gmp_gmi_tx_ifg_s     cn78xxp1;
04888     struct cvmx_bgxx_gmp_gmi_tx_ifg_s     cnf75xx;
04889 };
04890 typedef union cvmx_bgxx_gmp_gmi_tx_ifg cvmx_bgxx_gmp_gmi_tx_ifg_t;

05266                                                          0.

05268                                                          affecting the CSR field.

05318                                                          software write requests are ignored and this bit remains at 0. This bit clears itself to

05325                                                          that value and any attempts to write are ignored. */

05338                                                          and

05721 /**
05722  * cvmx_bgx#_smu#_hg2_control
05723  *
05724  * HiGig2 TX- and RX-enable are normally set together for HiGig2 messaging. Setting just the TX
05725  * or RX bit results in only the HG2 message transmit or receive capability.
05726  *
05727  * Setting [PHYS_EN] and [LOGL_EN] to 1 allows link PAUSE or backpressure to PKO as per the
05728  * received HiGig2 message. Setting these fields to 0 disables link PAUSE and backpressure to PKO
05729  * in response to received messages.
05730  *
05731  * BGX()_SMU()_TX_CTL[HG_EN] must be set (to enable HiGig) whenever either [HG2TX_EN] or
05732  * [HG2RX_EN] are set. BGX()_SMU()_RX_UDD_SKP[LEN] must be set to 16 (to select HiGig2)
05733  * whenever either [HG2TX_EN] or [HG2RX_EN] are set.
05734  *
05735  * BGX()_CMR_RX_OVR_BP[EN]<0> must be set and BGX()_CMR_RX_OVR_BP[BP]<0> must be cleared
05736  * to 0 (to forcibly disable hardware-automatic 802.3 PAUSE packet generation) with the HiGig2
05737  * Protocol when [HG2TX_EN] = 0. (The HiGig2 protocol is indicated
05738  * by BGX()_SMU()_TX_CTL[HG_EN] = 1 and BGX()_SMU()_RX_UDD_SKP[LEN]=16.) Hardware
05739  * can only autogenerate backpressure via HiGig2 messages (optionally, when [HG2TX_EN] = 1) with
05740  * the HiGig2 protocol.
05741  */
05742 union cvmx_bgxx_smux_hg2_control {
05743     uint64_t u64;
05744     struct cvmx_bgxx_smux_hg2_control_s {
05745 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
05746     uint64_t reserved_19_63               : 45;
05747     uint64_t hg2tx_en                     : 1;  /**< Enable transmission of HG2 physical and logical messages. When set, also disables hardware
05748                                                          autogenerated 802.3 PAUSE and PFC frames. (CNXXXX cannot generate proper 802.3 or
05749                                                          PFC frames in HiGig2 mode.) */
05750     uint64_t hg2rx_en                     : 1;  /**< Enable extraction and processing of HG2 message packet from RX flow. Physical and logical
05751                                                          PAUSE information is used to PAUSE physical-link, backpressure PKO. This field must be set
05752                                                          when HiGig2 messages are present in the receive stream. This bit is also forwarded to CMR
05753                                                          so it can generate the required deferring signals to SMU TX and backpressure signals to
05754                                                          PKO. */
05755     uint64_t phys_en                      : 1;  /**< Physical-link backpressure enable for received physical HiGig2 messages. This bit enables
05756                                                          the SMU TX to CMR HG2 deferring counter to be set every time SMU RX receives and filters
05757                                                          out a valid physical HG2 message. */
05758     uint64_t logl_en                      : 16; /**< 16-bit logical-link backpressure enables for received HiGig2 messages or PFC packets. */
05759 #else
05760     uint64_t logl_en                      : 16;
05761     uint64_t phys_en                      : 1;
05762     uint64_t hg2rx_en                     : 1;
05763     uint64_t hg2tx_en                     : 1;
05764     uint64_t reserved_19_63               : 45;
05765 #endif
05766     } s;
05767     struct cvmx_bgxx_smux_hg2_control_s   cn73xx;
05768     struct cvmx_bgxx_smux_hg2_control_s   cn78xx;
05769     struct cvmx_bgxx_smux_hg2_control_s   cn78xxp1;
05770     struct cvmx_bgxx_smux_hg2_control_s   cnf75xx;
05771 };
05772 typedef union cvmx_bgxx_smux_hg2_control cvmx_bgxx_smux_hg2_control_t;

05845 /**
05846  * cvmx_bgx#_smu#_rx_decision
05847  *
05848  * This register specifies the byte count used to determine when to accept or to filter a packet.
05849  * As each byte in a packet is received by BGX, the L2 byte count (i.e. the number of bytes from
05850  * the beginning of the L2 header (DMAC)) is compared against CNT. In normal operation, the L2
05851  * header begins after the PREAMBLE + SFD (BGX()_SMU()_RX_FRM_CTL[PRE_CHK] = 1) and any
05852  * optional UDD skip data (BGX()_SMU()_RX_UDD_SKP[LEN]).
05853  */
05854 union cvmx_bgxx_smux_rx_decision {
05855     uint64_t u64;
05856     struct cvmx_bgxx_smux_rx_decision_s {
05857 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
05858     uint64_t reserved_5_63                : 59;
05859     uint64_t cnt                          : 5;  /**< The byte count to decide when to accept or filter a packet. */
05860 #else
05861     uint64_t cnt                          : 5;
05862     uint64_t reserved_5_63                : 59;
05863 #endif
05864     } s;
05865     struct cvmx_bgxx_smux_rx_decision_s   cn73xx;
05866     struct cvmx_bgxx_smux_rx_decision_s   cn78xx;
05867     struct cvmx_bgxx_smux_rx_decision_s   cn78xxp1;
05868     struct cvmx_bgxx_smux_rx_decision_s   cnf75xx;
05869 };
05870 typedef union cvmx_bgxx_smux_rx_decision cvmx_bgxx_smux_rx_decision_t;

05908 /**
05909  * cvmx_bgx#_smu#_rx_frm_ctl
05910  *
05911  * This register controls the handling of the frames.
05912  * The [CTL_BCK] and [CTL_DRP] bits control how the hardware handles incoming PAUSE packets. The
05913  * most
05914  * common modes of operation:
05915  * _ [CTL_BCK] = 1, [CTL_DRP] = 1: hardware handles everything
05916  * _ [CTL_BCK] = 0, [CTL_DRP] = 0: software sees all PAUSE frames
05917  * _ [CTL_BCK] = 0, [CTL_DRP] = 1: all PAUSE frames are completely ignored
05918  *
05919  * These control bits should be set to [CTL_BCK] = 0, [CTL_DRP] = 0 in half-duplex mode. Since
05920  * PAUSE
05921  * packets only apply to full duplex operation, any PAUSE packet would constitute an exception
05922  * which should be handled by the processing cores. PAUSE packets should not be forwarded.
05923  */
05924 union cvmx_bgxx_smux_rx_frm_ctl {
05925     uint64_t u64;
05926     struct cvmx_bgxx_smux_rx_frm_ctl_s {
05927 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
05928     uint64_t reserved_13_63               : 51;
05929     uint64_t ptp_mode                     : 1;  /**< Timestamp mode. When [PTP_MODE] is set, a 64-bit timestamp is prepended to every incoming
05930                                                          packet.
05931                                                          The timestamp bytes are added to the packet in such a way as to not modify the packet's
05932                                                          receive byte count. This implies that the BGX()_SMU()_RX_JABBER,
05933                                                          BGX()_SMU()_RX_DECISION, and BGX()_SMU()_RX_UDD_SKP do not require any
05934                                                          adjustment as they operate on the received packet size. When the packet reaches PKI, its
05935                                                          size reflects the additional bytes and is subject to the following restrictions:
05936                                                          If [PTP_MODE] = 1 and [PRE_CHK] = 1, [PRE_STRP] must be 1.
05937                                                          If [PTP_MODE] = 1:
05938                                                          * PKI_CL()_PKIND()_SKIP[FCS_SKIP,INST_SKIP] should be increased by 8.
05939                                                          * PKI_CL()_PKIND()_CFG[HG_EN] should be 0.
05940                                                          * PKI_FRM_LEN_CHK()[MAXLEN] should be increased by 8.
05941                                                          * PKI_FRM_LEN_CHK()[MINLEN] should be increased by 8.
05942                                                          * PKI_TAG_INC()_MASK should be adjusted. */
05943     uint64_t reserved_6_11                : 6;
05944     uint64_t ctl_smac                     : 1;  /**< Control PAUSE frames can match station SMAC. */
05945     uint64_t ctl_mcst                     : 1;  /**< Control PAUSE frames can match globally assigned multicast address. */
05946     uint64_t ctl_bck                      : 1;  /**< Forward PAUSE information to TX block. */
05947     uint64_t ctl_drp                      : 1;  /**< Drop control PAUSE frames. */
05948     uint64_t pre_strp                     : 1;  /**< Strip off the preamble (when present).
05949                                                          0 = PREAMBLE + SFD is sent to core as part of frame.
05950                                                          1 = PREAMBLE + SFD is dropped.
05951                                                          [PRE_CHK] must be set to enable this and all PREAMBLE features.
05952                                                          If [PTP_MODE] = 1 and [PRE_CHK] = 1, [PRE_STRP] must be 1.
05953                                                          When [PRE_CHK] is set (indicating that the PREAMBLE will be sent), [PRE_STRP] determines
05954                                                          if
05955                                                          the PREAMBLE+SFD bytes are thrown away or sent to the core as part of the packet. In
05956                                                          either mode, the PREAMBLE+SFD bytes are not counted toward the packet size when checking
05957                                                          against the MIN and MAX bounds. Furthermore, the bytes are skipped when locating the start
05958                                                          of the L2 header for DMAC and control frame recognition. */
05959     uint64_t pre_chk                      : 1;  /**< Check the preamble for correctness.
05960                                                          This port is configured to send a valid 802.3 PREAMBLE to begin every frame. BGX checks
05961                                                          that a valid PREAMBLE is received. When a problem does occur within
05962                                                          the PREAMBLE sequence, the frame is marked as bad and not sent into the core. The
05963                                                          BGX()_SMU()_RX_INT[PCTERR] interrupt is also raised.
05964                                                          When BGX()_SMU()_TX_CTL[HG_EN] is set, [PRE_CHK] must be 0.
05965                                                          If [PTP_MODE] = 1 and [PRE_CHK] = 1, [PRE_STRP] must be 1. */
05966 #else
05967     uint64_t pre_chk                      : 1;
05968     uint64_t pre_strp                     : 1;
05969     uint64_t ctl_drp                      : 1;
05970     uint64_t ctl_bck                      : 1;
05971     uint64_t ctl_mcst                     : 1;
05972     uint64_t ctl_smac                     : 1;
05973     uint64_t reserved_6_11                : 6;
05974     uint64_t ptp_mode                     : 1;
05975     uint64_t reserved_13_63               : 51;
05976 #endif
05977     } s;
05978     struct cvmx_bgxx_smux_rx_frm_ctl_s    cn73xx;
05979     struct cvmx_bgxx_smux_rx_frm_ctl_s    cn78xx;
05980     struct cvmx_bgxx_smux_rx_frm_ctl_s    cn78xxp1;
05981     struct cvmx_bgxx_smux_rx_frm_ctl_s    cnf75xx;
05982 };
05983 typedef union cvmx_bgxx_smux_rx_frm_ctl cvmx_bgxx_smux_rx_frm_ctl_t;

05985 /**
05986  * cvmx_bgx#_smu#_rx_int
05987  *
05988  * SMU Interrupt Register.
05989  *
05990  */
05991 union cvmx_bgxx_smux_rx_int {
05992     uint64_t u64;
05993     struct cvmx_bgxx_smux_rx_int_s {
05994 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
05995     uint64_t reserved_12_63               : 52;
05996     uint64_t hg2cc                        : 1;  /**< HiGig2 received message CRC or control-character error. Set when either a CRC8 error is
05997                                                          detected, or when a control character is found in the message bytes after the K.SOM.
05998                                                          HG2CC has higher priority than HG2FLD, which means that a HiGig2 message that results in
05999                                                          HG2CC getting set never sets HG2FLD. */
06000     uint64_t hg2fld                       : 1;  /**< HiGig2 received message field error:
06001                                                          MSG_TYPE field not 0x0, i.e. it is not a flow-control message, which is the only defined
06002                                                          type for HiGig2.
06003                                                          FWD_TYPE field not 0x0, i.e. it is not a link-level message, which is the only defined
06004                                                          type for HiGig2.
06005                                                          FC_OBJECT field is neither 0x0 for physical link, nor 0x2 for logical link. Those are the
06006                                                          only two defined types in HiGig2 */
06007     uint64_t bad_term                     : 1;  /**< Frame is terminated by control character other than /T/. (XAUI/RXAUI mode only) The error
06008                                                          propagation control character /E/ will be included as part of the frame and does not cause
06009                                                          a frame termination. */
06010     uint64_t bad_seq                      : 1;  /**< Reserved sequence detected. (XAUI/RXAUI mode only) */
06011     uint64_t rem_fault                    : 1;  /**< Remote-fault sequence detected. (XAUI/RXAUI mode only) */
06012     uint64_t loc_fault                    : 1;  /**< Local-fault sequence detected. (XAUI/RXAUI mode only) */
06013     uint64_t rsverr                       : 1;  /**< Reserved opcodes. */
06014     uint64_t pcterr                       : 1;  /**< Bad preamble/protocol. In XAUI/RXAUI mode, the column of data that was bad is logged in
06015                                                          BGX()_SMU()_RX_BAD_COL_LO and BGX()_SMU()_RX_BAD_COL_HI.
06016                                                          PCTERR checks that the frame begins with a valid
06017                                                          PREAMBLE sequence. Does not check the number of PREAMBLE cycles. */
06018     uint64_t skperr                       : 1;  /**< Skipper error. */
06019     uint64_t rcverr                       : 1;  /**< Frame was received with data-reception error. */
06020     uint64_t fcserr                       : 1;  /**< Frame was received with FCS/CRC error */
06021     uint64_t jabber                       : 1;  /**< Frame was received with length > sys_length. An RX Jabber error indicates that a packet
06022                                                          was received which is longer than the maximum allowed packet as defined by the system. BGX
06023                                                          terminates the packet with an EOP on the beat on which JABBER was exceeded. The beat on
06024                                                          which JABBER was exceeded is left unchanged and all subsequent data beats are dropped.
06025                                                          Failure to truncate could lead to system instability. */
06026 #else
06027     uint64_t jabber                       : 1;
06028     uint64_t fcserr                       : 1;
06029     uint64_t rcverr                       : 1;
06030     uint64_t skperr                       : 1;
06031     uint64_t pcterr                       : 1;
06032     uint64_t rsverr                       : 1;
06033     uint64_t loc_fault                    : 1;
06034     uint64_t rem_fault                    : 1;
06035     uint64_t bad_seq                      : 1;
06036     uint64_t bad_term                     : 1;
06037     uint64_t hg2fld                       : 1;
06038     uint64_t hg2cc                        : 1;
06039     uint64_t reserved_12_63               : 52;
06040 #endif
06041     } s;
06042     struct cvmx_bgxx_smux_rx_int_s        cn73xx;
06043     struct cvmx_bgxx_smux_rx_int_s        cn78xx;
06044     struct cvmx_bgxx_smux_rx_int_s        cn78xxp1;
06045     struct cvmx_bgxx_smux_rx_int_s        cnf75xx;

06100 #else

06167 /**
06168  * cvmx_bgx#_smu#_tx_ctl
06169  */
06170 union cvmx_bgxx_smux_tx_ctl {
06171     uint64_t u64;
06172     struct cvmx_bgxx_smux_tx_ctl_s {
06173 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
06174     uint64_t reserved_31_63               : 33;
06175     uint64_t spu_mrk_cnt                  : 20; /**< 40GBASE-R transmit marker interval count. Specifies the interval (number of 66-bit BASE-R
06176                                                          blocks) at which the LMAC transmit logic inserts 40GBASE-R alignment markers. An internal
06177                                                          counter in SMU is initialized to this value, counts down for each BASE-R block transmitted
06178                                                          by the LMAC, and wraps back to the initial value from 0. The LMAC transmit logic inserts
06179                                                          alignment markers for lanes 0, 1, 2 and 3, respectively, in the last four BASE-R blocks
06180                                                          before the counter wraps (3, 2, 1, 0). The default value corresponds to an alignment
06181                                                          marker period of 16363 blocks (exclusive) per lane, as specified in 802.3ba-2010. The
06182                                                          default value should always be used for normal operation. */
06183     uint64_t hg_pause_hgi                 : 2;  /**< HGI field for hardware-generated HiGig PAUSE packets. */
06184     uint64_t hg_en                        : 1;  /**< Enable HiGig mode.
06185                                                          When this field is set and BGX()_SMU()_RX_UDD_SKP[LEN] = 12, the interface is in
06186                                                          HiGig/HiGig+ mode and the following must be set:
06187                                                          * BGX()_SMU()_RX_FRM_CTL[PRE_CHK] = 0.
06188                                                          * BGX()_SMU()_RX_UDD_SKP[FCSSEL] = 0.
06189                                                          * BGX()_SMU()_RX_UDD_SKP[LEN] = 12.
06190                                                          * BGX()_SMU()_TX_APPEND[PREAMBLE] = 0.
06191                                                          When this field is set and BGX()_SMU()_RX_UDD_SKP[LEN] = 16, the interface is in
06192                                                          HiGig2 mode and the following must be set:
06193                                                          * BGX()_SMU()_RX_FRM_CTL[PRE_CHK] = 0.
06194                                                          * BGX()_SMU()_RX_UDD_SKP[FCSSEL] = 0.
06195                                                          * BGX()_SMU()_RX_UDD_SKP[LEN] = 16.
06196                                                          * BGX()_SMU()_TX_APPEND[PREAMBLE] = 0.
06197                                                          * BGX()_SMU()_CBFC_CTL[RX_EN] = 0.
06198                                                          * BGX()_SMU()_CBFC_CTL[TX_EN] = 0. */
06199     uint64_t l2p_bp_conv                  : 1;  /**< If set, causes TX to generate 802.3 pause packets when CMR applies logical backpressure
06200                                                          (XOFF), if and only if BGX()_SMU()_CBFC_CTL[TX_EN] is clear and
06201                                                          BGX()_SMU()_HG2_CONTROL[HG2TX_EN] is clear. */
06202     uint64_t ls_byp                       : 1;  /**< Bypass the link status, as determined by the XGMII receiver, and set the link status of
06203                                                          the transmitter to LS. */
06204     uint64_t ls                           : 2;  /**< Link status.
06205                                                          0 = Link OK; link runs normally. RS passes MAC data to PCS.
06206                                                          1 = Local fault. RS layer sends continuous remote fault sequences.
06207                                                          2 = Remote fault. RS layer sends continuous idle sequences.
06208                                                          3 = Link drain. RS layer drops full packets to allow BGX and PKO to drain their FIFOs. */
06209     uint64_t reserved_3_3                 : 1;
06210     uint64_t x4a_dis                      : 1;  /**< Disable 4-byte SOP align (effectively force 8-byte SOP align) for all 10G variants
06211                                                          (XAUI, RXAUI, 10G). */
06212     uint64_t uni_en                       : 1;  /**< Enable unidirectional mode (IEEE Clause 66). */
06213     uint64_t dic_en                       : 1;  /**< Enable the deficit idle counter for IFG averaging. */
06214 #else
06215     uint64_t dic_en                       : 1;
06216     uint64_t uni_en                       : 1;
06217     uint64_t x4a_dis                      : 1;
06218     uint64_t reserved_3_3                 : 1;
06219     uint64_t ls                           : 2;
06220     uint64_t ls_byp                       : 1;
06221     uint64_t l2p_bp_conv                  : 1;
06222     uint64_t hg_en                        : 1;
06223     uint64_t hg_pause_hgi                 : 2;
06224     uint64_t spu_mrk_cnt                  : 20;
06225     uint64_t reserved_31_63               : 33;
06226 #endif
06227     } s;

06229     struct cvmx_bgxx_smux_tx_ctl_s        cn78xx;

06231     struct cvmx_bgxx_smux_tx_ctl_s        cnf75xx;

06235 /**
06236  * cvmx_bgx#_smu#_tx_ifg
06237  *
06238  * Programming IFG1 and IFG2:
06239  * * For XAUI/RXAUI/10Gbs/40Gbs systems that require IEEE 802.3 compatibility, the IFG1+IFG2 sum
06240  * must be 12.
06241  * * In loopback mode, the IFG1+IFG2 of local and remote parties must match exactly; otherwise
06242  * one of the two sides' loopback FIFO will overrun: BGX()_SMU()_TX_INT[LB_OVRFLW].
06243  */
06244 union cvmx_bgxx_smux_tx_ifg {
06245     uint64_t u64;
06246     struct cvmx_bgxx_smux_tx_ifg_s {
06247 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
06248     uint64_t reserved_8_63                : 56;
06249     uint64_t ifg2                         : 4;  /**< 1/2 of the interframe gap timing (in IFG2*8 bits). */
06250     uint64_t ifg1                         : 4;  /**< 1/2 of the interframe gap timing (in IFG1*8 bits). */
06251 #else
06252     uint64_t ifg1                         : 4;
06253     uint64_t ifg2                         : 4;
06254     uint64_t reserved_8_63                : 56;
06255 #endif
06256     } s;
06257     struct cvmx_bgxx_smux_tx_ifg_s        cn73xx;
06258     struct cvmx_bgxx_smux_tx_ifg_s        cn78xx;
06259     struct cvmx_bgxx_smux_tx_ifg_s        cn78xxp1;
06260     struct cvmx_bgxx_smux_tx_ifg_s        cnf75xx;
06261 };
06262 typedef union cvmx_bgxx_smux_tx_ifg cvmx_bgxx_smux_tx_ifg_t;

06275                                                          256 cycles so it faked a commit to CMR. */

06277     uint64_t undflw                       : 1;  /**< TX underflow. */

06285 #endif

06517 /**
06518  * cvmx_bgx#_spu#_an_adv
06519  *
06520  * Software programs this register with the contents of the AN-link code word base page to be
06521  * transmitted during autonegotiation. (See Std 802.3 section 73.6 for details.) Any write
06522  * operations to this register prior to completion of autonegotiation, as indicated by
06523  * BGX()_SPU()_AN_STATUS[AN_COMPLETE], should be followed by a renegotiation in order for
06524  * the new values to take effect. Renegotiation is initiated by setting
06525  * BGX()_SPU()_AN_CONTROL[AN_RESTART]. Once autonegotiation has completed, software can
06526  * examine this register along with BGX()_SPU()_AN_LP_BASE to determine the highest
06527  * common denominator technology.
06528  */
06529 union cvmx_bgxx_spux_an_adv {
06530     uint64_t u64;
06531     struct cvmx_bgxx_spux_an_adv_s {
06532 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
06533     uint64_t reserved_48_63               : 16;
06534     uint64_t fec_req                      : 1;  /**< FEC requested. */
06535     uint64_t fec_able                     : 1;  /**< FEC ability. */
06536     uint64_t arsv                         : 19; /**< Technology ability. Reserved bits, should always be 0. */
06537     uint64_t a100g_cr10                   : 1;  /**< 100GBASE-CR10 ability. Should always be 0; 100GBASE-R is not supported. */
06538     uint64_t a40g_cr4                     : 1;  /**< 40GBASE-CR4 ability. */
06539     uint64_t a40g_kr4                     : 1;  /**< 40GBASE-KR4 ability. */
06540     uint64_t a10g_kr                      : 1;  /**< 10GBASE-KR ability. */
06541     uint64_t a10g_kx4                     : 1;  /**< 10GBASE-KX4 ability. */
06542     uint64_t a1g_kx                       : 1;  /**< 1000BASE-KX ability. Should always be 0; Autonegotiation is not supported for 1000Base-KX. */
06543     uint64_t t                            : 5;  /**< Transmitted nonce. This field is automatically updated with a pseudo-random value on entry
06544                                                          to the AN ability detect state. */
06545     uint64_t np                           : 1;  /**< Next page. Always 0; extended next pages are not used for 10G+ Autonegotiation. */
06546     uint64_t ack                          : 1;  /**< Acknowledge. Always 0 in this register. */
06547     uint64_t rf                           : 1;  /**< Remote fault. */
06548     uint64_t xnp_able                     : 1;  /**< Extended next page ability. */
06549     uint64_t asm_dir                      : 1;  /**< Asymmetric PAUSE. */
06550     uint64_t pause                        : 1;  /**< PAUSE ability. */
06551     uint64_t e                            : 5;  /**< Echoed nonce. Provides the echoed-nonce value to use when ACK = 0 in transmitted DME page.
06552                                                          Should always be 0x0. */
06553     uint64_t s                            : 5;  /**< Selector. Should be 0x1 (encoding for IEEE Std 802.3). */
06554 #else
06555     uint64_t s                            : 5;
06556     uint64_t e                            : 5;
06557     uint64_t pause                        : 1;
06558     uint64_t asm_dir                      : 1;
06559     uint64_t xnp_able                     : 1;
06560     uint64_t rf                           : 1;
06561     uint64_t ack                          : 1;
06562     uint64_t np                           : 1;
06563     uint64_t t                            : 5;
06564     uint64_t a1g_kx                       : 1;
06565     uint64_t a10g_kx4                     : 1;
06566     uint64_t a10g_kr                      : 1;
06567     uint64_t a40g_kr4                     : 1;
06568     uint64_t a40g_cr4                     : 1;
06569     uint64_t a100g_cr10                   : 1;
06570     uint64_t arsv                         : 19;
06571     uint64_t fec_able                     : 1;
06572     uint64_t fec_req                      : 1;
06573     uint64_t reserved_48_63               : 16;
06574 #endif
06575     } s;
06576     struct cvmx_bgxx_spux_an_adv_s        cn73xx;
06577     struct cvmx_bgxx_spux_an_adv_s        cn78xx;
06578     struct cvmx_bgxx_spux_an_adv_s        cn78xxp1;
06579     struct cvmx_bgxx_spux_an_adv_s        cnf75xx;

06587  * during autonegotiation and are valid when BGX()_SPU()_AN_STATUS[AN_COMPLETE] is set.
06588  * At that time, one of the port type bits ([N100G_CR10], [N40G_CR4], [N40G_KR4], [N10G_KR],
06589  * [N10G_KX4],

06591  * then [FEC] will be set to indicate that FEC operation has been negotiated, and will be
06592  * clear otherwise.

06594 union cvmx_bgxx_spux_an_bp_status {

06602     uint64_t n40g_kr4                     : 1;  /**< 40GBASE-KR4 negotiated. */
06603     uint64_t fec                          : 1;  /**< BASE-R FEC negotiated. */
06604     uint64_t n10g_kr                      : 1;  /**< 10GBASE-KR negotiated. */
06605     uint64_t n10g_kx4                     : 1;  /**< 10GBASE-KX4 or CX4 negotiated (XAUI). */
06606     uint64_t n1g_kx                       : 1;  /**< 1000BASE-KX negotiated. */
06607     uint64_t bp_an_able                   : 1;  /**< Backplane or BASE-R copper AN Ability; always 1. */
06608 #else
06609     uint64_t bp_an_able                   : 1;
06610     uint64_t n1g_kx                       : 1;
06611     uint64_t n10g_kx4                     : 1;
06612     uint64_t n10g_kr                      : 1;
06613     uint64_t fec                          : 1;
06614     uint64_t n40g_kr4                     : 1;

06616     uint64_t reserved_7_7                 : 1;
06617     uint64_t n100g_cr10                   : 1;
06618     uint64_t reserved_9_63                : 55;
06619 #endif
06620     } s;
06621     struct cvmx_bgxx_spux_an_bp_status_s  cn73xx;
06622     struct cvmx_bgxx_spux_an_bp_status_s  cn78xx;

06628 /**
06629  * cvmx_bgx#_spu#_an_control
06630  */
06631 union cvmx_bgxx_spux_an_control {
06632     uint64_t u64;
06633     struct cvmx_bgxx_spux_an_control_s {
06634 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
06635     uint64_t reserved_16_63               : 48;
06636     uint64_t an_reset                     : 1;  /**< Autonegotiation reset. Setting this bit or BGX()_SPU()_CONTROL1[RESET] to 1
06637                                                          causes the following to happen:
06638                                                          * Resets the logical PCS (LPCS)
06639                                                          * Sets the Std 802.3 PCS, FEC and AN registers for the LPCS to their default states
06640                                                          * Resets the associated SerDes lanes.
06641                                                          It takes up to 32 coprocessor-clock cycles to reset the LPCS, after which RESET is
06642                                                          automatically cleared. */
06643     uint64_t reserved_14_14               : 1;
06644     uint64_t xnp_en                       : 1;  /**< Extended next-page enable. */

06647                                                          in RXAUI mode. */
06648     uint64_t reserved_10_11               : 2;
06649     uint64_t an_restart                   : 1;  /**< Autonegotiation restart. Writing a 1 to this bit restarts the autonegotiation process if
06650                                                          [AN_EN] is also set. This is a self-clearing bit. */
06651     uint64_t reserved_0_8                 : 9;
06652 #else
06653     uint64_t reserved_0_8                 : 9;
06654     uint64_t an_restart                   : 1;
06655     uint64_t reserved_10_11               : 2;
06656     uint64_t an_en                        : 1;
06657     uint64_t xnp_en                       : 1;
06658     uint64_t reserved_14_14               : 1;
06659     uint64_t an_reset                     : 1;
06660     uint64_t reserved_16_63               : 48;
06661 #endif
06662     } s;

06822 /**
06823  * cvmx_bgx#_spu#_an_xnp_tx
06824  *
06825  * Software programs this register with the contents of the AN message next page or unformatted
06826  * next page link code word to be transmitted during autonegotiation. Next page exchange occurs
06827  * after the base link code words have been exchanged if either end of the link segment sets the
06828  * NP bit to 1, indicating that it has at least one next page to send. Once initiated, next page
06829  * exchange continues until both ends of the link segment set their NP bits to 0. See section
06830  * 802.3 section 73.7.7 for details.
06831  */
06832 union cvmx_bgxx_spux_an_xnp_tx {
06833     uint64_t u64;

06835 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD

06837     uint64_t u                            : 32; /**< Unformatted code field. When the MP bit is set, this field contains the 32-bit unformatted
06838                                                          code field of the message next page. When MP is clear, this field contains the upper 32
06839                                                          bits of the 43-bit unformatted code field of the unformatted next page. */
06840     uint64_t np                           : 1;  /**< Next page. */
06841     uint64_t ack                          : 1;  /**< Acknowledge: Always 0 in this register. */
06842     uint64_t mp                           : 1;  /**< Message page. Set to indicate that this register contains a message next page. Clear to
06843                                                          indicate that the register contains an unformatted next page. */
06844     uint64_t ack2                         : 1;  /**< Acknowledge 2. Indicates that the receiver is able to act on the information (or perform
06845                                                          the task) defined in the message. */
06846     uint64_t toggle                       : 1;  /**< This bit is ignored by hardware. The value of the TOGGLE bit in transmitted next pages is
06847                                                          automatically generated by hardware. */
06848     uint64_t m_u                          : 11; /**< Message/unformatted code field: When the MP bit is set, this field contains the message
06849                                                          code field (M) of the message next page. When MP is clear, this field contains the lower
06850                                                          11 bits of the 43-bit unformatted code field of the unformatted next page. */
06851 #else
06852     uint64_t m_u                          : 11;
06853     uint64_t toggle                       : 1;
06854     uint64_t ack2                         : 1;
06855     uint64_t mp                           : 1;
06856     uint64_t ack                          : 1;
06857     uint64_t np                           : 1;
06858     uint64_t u                            : 32;
06859     uint64_t reserved_48_63               : 16;
06860 #endif
06861     } s;

06911 /**
06912  * cvmx_bgx#_spu#_br_bip_err_cnt
06913  *
06914  * This register implements the Std 802.3 BIP error-counter registers for PCS lanes 0-3
06915  * (3.200-3.203). It is valid only when the LPCS type is 40GBASE-R
06916  * (BGX()_CMR()_CONFIG[LMAC_TYPE] = 0x4), and always returns 0x0 for all other LPCS
06917  * types. The counters are indexed by the RX PCS lane number based on the Alignment Marker
06918  * detected on each lane and captured in BGX()_SPU()_BR_LANE_MAP. Each counter counts the
06919  * BIP errors for its PCS lane, and is held at all ones in case of overflow. The counters are
06920  * reset to all 0s when this register is read by software.
06921  *
06922  * The reset operation takes precedence over the increment operation; if the register is read on
06923  * the same clock cycle as an increment operation, the counter is reset to all 0s and the
06924  * increment operation is lost. The counters are writable for test purposes, rather than read-
06925  * only as specified in Std 802.3.
06926  */
06927 union cvmx_bgxx_spux_br_bip_err_cnt {

06932     uint64_t bip_err_cnt_ln2              : 16; /**< BIP error counter for lane on which PCS lane 2 markers are received. */
06933     uint64_t bip_err_cnt_ln1              : 16; /**< BIP error counter for lane on which PCS lane 1 markers are received. */
06934     uint64_t bip_err_cnt_ln0              : 16; /**< BIP error counter for lane on which PCS lane 0 markers are received. */
06935 #else
06936     uint64_t bip_err_cnt_ln0              : 16;
06937     uint64_t bip_err_cnt_ln1              : 16;
06938     uint64_t bip_err_cnt_ln2              : 16;
06939     uint64_t bip_err_cnt_ln3              : 16;
06940 #endif
06941     } s;
06942     struct cvmx_bgxx_spux_br_bip_err_cnt_s cn73xx;
06943     struct cvmx_bgxx_spux_br_bip_err_cnt_s cn78xx;

06945     struct cvmx_bgxx_spux_br_bip_err_cnt_s cnf75xx;

06949 /**
06950  * cvmx_bgx#_spu#_br_lane_map
06951  *
06952  * This register implements the Std 802.3 lane 0-3 mapping registers (3.400-3.403). It is valid
06953  * only when the LPCS type is 40GBASE-R (BGX()_CMR()_CONFIG[LMAC_TYPE] = 0x4), and always
06954  * returns 0x0 for all other LPCS types. The LNx_MAPPING field for each programmed PCS lane
06955  * (called service interface in 802.3ba-2010) is valid when that lane has achieved alignment
06956  * marker lock on the receive side (i.e. the associated
06957  * BGX()_SPU()_BR_ALGN_STATUS[MARKER_LOCK] = 1), and is invalid otherwise. When valid, it
06958  * returns the actual detected receive PCS lane number based on the received alignment marker
06959  * contents received on that service interface.
06960  *
06961  * The mapping is flexible because Std 802.3 allows multilane BASE-R receive lanes to be re-
06962  * ordered. Note that for the transmit side, each PCS lane is mapped to a physical SerDes lane
06963  * based on the programming of BGX()_CMR()_CONFIG[LANE_TO_SDS]. For the receive side,
06964  * BGX()_CMR()_CONFIG[LANE_TO_SDS] specifies the service interface to physical SerDes
06965  * lane mapping, and this register specifies the PCS lane to service interface mapping.
06966  */
06967 union cvmx_bgxx_spux_br_lane_map {

06970 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
06971     uint64_t reserved_54_63               : 10;

06973     uint64_t reserved_38_47               : 10;
06974     uint64_t ln2_mapping                  : 6;  /**< PCS lane number received on service interface 2 */
06975     uint64_t reserved_22_31               : 10;
06976     uint64_t ln1_mapping                  : 6;  /**< PCS lane number received on service interface 1 */
06977     uint64_t reserved_6_15                : 10;
06978     uint64_t ln0_mapping                  : 6;  /**< PCS lane number received on service interface 0 */
06979 #else
06980     uint64_t ln0_mapping                  : 6;
06981     uint64_t reserved_6_15                : 10;
06982     uint64_t ln1_mapping                  : 6;
06983     uint64_t reserved_22_31               : 10;
06984     uint64_t ln2_mapping                  : 6;
06985     uint64_t reserved_38_47               : 10;
06986     uint64_t ln3_mapping                  : 6;
06987     uint64_t reserved_54_63               : 10;
06988 #endif
06989     } s;
06990     struct cvmx_bgxx_spux_br_lane_map_s   cn73xx;
06991     struct cvmx_bgxx_spux_br_lane_map_s   cn78xx;

07023 /**
07024  * cvmx_bgx#_spu#_br_pmd_ld_cup
07025  *
07026  * This register implements 802.3 MDIO register 1.153 for 10GBASE-R (when
07027  * BGX()_CMR()_CONFIG[LMAC_TYPE] = 10G_R)
07028  * and MDIO registers 1.1300-1.1303 for 40GBASE-R (when
07029  * BGX()_CMR()_CONFIG[LMAC_TYPE] = 40G_R). It is automatically cleared at the start of training.
07030  * When link training
07031  * is in progress, each field reflects the contents of the coefficient update field in the
07032  * associated lane's outgoing training frame. The fields in this register are read/write even
07033  * though they are specified as read-only in 802.3.
07034  *
07035  * If BGX()_SPU_DBG_CONTROL[BR_PMD_TRAIN_SOFT_EN] is set, then this register must be updated
07036  * by software during link training and hardware updates are disabled. If
07037  * BGX()_SPU_DBG_CONTROL[BR_PMD_TRAIN_SOFT_EN] is clear, this register is automatically
07038  * updated by hardware, and it should not be written by software. The lane fields in this
07039  * register are indexed by logical PCS lane ID.
07040  *
07041  * The lane 0 field (LN0_*) is valid for both
07042  * 10GBASE-R and 40GBASE-R. The remaining fields (LN1_*, LN2_*, LN3_*) are only valid for
07043  * 40GBASE-R.
07044  */
07045 union cvmx_bgxx_spux_br_pmd_ld_cup {
07046     uint64_t u64;
07047     struct cvmx_bgxx_spux_br_pmd_ld_cup_s {
