07050                                                          10GBASE-R. */
07051     uint64_t ln2_cup                      : 16; /**< PCS lane 2 coefficient update: format defined by BGX_SPU_BR_TRAIN_CUP_S. Not valid for
07052                                                          10GBASE-R. */
07053     uint64_t ln1_cup                      : 16; /**< PCS lane 1 coefficient update: format defined by BGX_SPU_BR_TRAIN_CUP_S. Not valid for
07054                                                          10GBASE-R. */
07055     uint64_t ln0_cup                      : 16; /**< PCS lane 0 coefficient update: format defined by BGX_SPU_BR_TRAIN_CUP_S. */
07056 #else

07060     uint64_t ln3_cup                      : 16;
07061 #endif

07266 #endif

07275 /**
07276  * cvmx_bgx#_spu#_br_status2
07277  *
07278  * This register implements a combination of the following Std 802.3 registers:
07279  * * BASE-R PCS status 2 (MDIO address 3.33).
07280  * * BASE-R BER high-order counter (MDIO address 3.44).
07281  * * Errored-blocks high-order counter (MDIO address 3.45).
07282  *
07283  * Note that the relative locations of some fields have been moved from Std 802.3 in order to
07284  * make the register layout more software friendly: the BER counter high-order and low-order bits
07285  * from sections 3.44 and 3.33 have been combined into the contiguous, 22-bit [BER_CNT] field;
07286  * likewise, the errored-blocks counter high-order and low-order bits from section 3.45 have been
07287  * combined into the contiguous, 22-bit [ERR_BLKS] field.
07288  */
07289 union cvmx_bgxx_spux_br_status2 {
07290     uint64_t u64;
07291     struct cvmx_bgxx_spux_br_status2_s {
07292 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
07293     uint64_t reserved_62_63               : 2;
07294     uint64_t err_blks                     : 22; /**< Errored-blocks counter. This is the BASE-R errored-blocks counter as defined by the
07295                                                          errored_block_count variable specified in Std 802.3 sections 49.2.14.2 and 82.2.18.2.4. It
07296                                                          increments by 1 on each block for which the BASE-R receive state machine, specified in Std
07297                                                          802.3 diagrams 49-15 and 82-15, enters the RX_E state.
07298                                                          Back-to-back blocks in the RX_E state are counted as transitions from RX_E to RX_E and
07299                                                          keep incrementing the counter. The counter is reset to all 0s after this register is read
07300                                                          by software.
07301                                                          The reset operation takes precedence over the increment operation: if the register is read
07302                                                          on the same clock cycle as an increment operation, the counter is reset to all 0s and the
07303                                                          increment operation is lost.
07304                                                          This field is writable for test purposes, rather than read-only as specified in Std 802.3. */
07305     uint64_t reserved_38_39               : 2;
07306     uint64_t ber_cnt                      : 22; /**< Bit-error-rate counter. This is the BASE-R BER counter as defined by the BER_COUNT
07307                                                          variable in Std 802.3 sections 49.2.14.2 and 82.2.18.2.4. The counter is reset to all 0s
07308                                                          after this register is read by software, and is held at all 1s in case of overflow.
07309                                                          The reset operation takes precedence over the increment operation: if the register is read
07310                                                          on the same clock cycle an increment operation, the counter is reset to all 0s and the
07311                                                          increment operation is lost.
07312                                                          This field is writable for test purposes, rather than read-only as specified in Std 802.3. */
07313     uint64_t latched_lock                 : 1;  /**< Latched-block lock.
07314                                                          0 = No block.
07315                                                          1 = 64/66 bit receiver for BASE-R has block lock.
07316                                                          This is a latching-low version of BGX()_SPU()_BR_STATUS1[BLK_LOCK]; it stays clear
07317                                                          until the register is read by software.
07318                                                          Note that in order to avoid read side effects, this is implemented as a write-1-to-set
07319                                                          bit, rather than latching low read-only as specified in 802.3. */
07320     uint64_t latched_ber                  : 1;  /**< Latched-high bit-error rate.
07321                                                          0 = Not a high BER.
07322                                                          1 = 64/66 bit receiver is detecting a high BER.
07323                                                          This is a latching-high version of BGX()_SPU()_BR_STATUS1[HI_BER]; it stays set until
07324                                                          the register is read by software.
07325                                                          Note that in order to avoid read side effects, this is implemented as a write-1-to-clear
07326                                                          bit, rather than latching high read-only as specified in 802.3. */
07327     uint64_t reserved_0_13                : 14;
07328 #else
07329     uint64_t reserved_0_13                : 14;
07330     uint64_t latched_ber                  : 1;
07331     uint64_t latched_lock                 : 1;
07332     uint64_t ber_cnt                      : 22;
07333     uint64_t reserved_38_39               : 2;
07334     uint64_t err_blks                     : 22;
07335     uint64_t reserved_62_63               : 2;
07336 #endif
07337     } s;
07338     struct cvmx_bgxx_spux_br_status2_s    cn73xx;
07339     struct cvmx_bgxx_spux_br_status2_s    cn78xx;
07340     struct cvmx_bgxx_spux_br_status2_s    cn78xxp1;
07341     struct cvmx_bgxx_spux_br_status2_s    cnf75xx;
07342 };
07343 typedef union cvmx_bgxx_spux_br_status2 cvmx_bgxx_spux_br_status2_t;

07349  *
07350  */
07351 union cvmx_bgxx_spux_br_tp_control {

07365                                                          test pattern. Setting this bit enables checking of that receive pattern. */

07367                                                          patterns are not supported. */

07377     uint64_t scramble_tp                  : 1;
07378     uint64_t reserved_8_63                : 56;
07379 #endif

07388 /**
07389  * cvmx_bgx#_spu#_br_tp_err_cnt
07390  *
07391  * This register provides the BASE-R PCS test-pattern error counter.
07392  *
07393  */
07394 union cvmx_bgxx_spux_br_tp_err_cnt {
07395     uint64_t u64;
07396     struct cvmx_bgxx_spux_br_tp_err_cnt_s {
07397 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
07398     uint64_t reserved_16_63               : 48;
07399     uint64_t err_cnt                      : 16; /**< Error counter. This 16-bit counter contains the number of errors received during a pattern
07400                                                          test. These bits are reset to all 0s when this register is read by software, and they are
07401                                                          held at all 1s in the case of overflow.
07402                                                          The test pattern methodology is described in Std 802.3, Sections 49.2.12 and 82.2.10. This
07403                                                          counter counts either block errors or bit errors dependent on the test mode (see Section
07404                                                          49.2.12). The reset operation takes precedence over the increment operation; if the
07405                                                          register is read on the same clock cycle as an increment operation, the counter is reset
07406                                                          to all 0s and the increment operation is lost. This field is writable for test purposes,
07407                                                          rather than read-only as specified in Std 802.3. */
07408 #else

07604 /**
07605  * cvmx_bgx#_spu#_fec_corr_blks01
07606  *
07607  * This register is valid only when the LPCS type is BASE-R
07608  * (BGX()_CMR()_CONFIG[LMAC_TYPE] = 0x3 or 0x4). The FEC corrected-block counters are
07609  * defined in Std 802.3 section 74.8.4.1. Each corrected-blocks counter increments by 1 for a
07610  * corrected FEC block, i.e. an FEC block that has been received with invalid parity on the
07611  * associated PCS lane and has been corrected by the FEC decoder. The counter is reset to all 0s
07612  * when the register is read, and held at all 1s in case of overflow.
07613  *
07614  * The reset operation takes precedence over the increment operation; if the register is read on
07615  * the same clock cycle as an increment operation, the counter is reset to all 0s and the
07616  * increment operation is lost. The counters are writable for test purposes, rather than read-
07617  * only as specified in Std 802.3.
07618  */
07619 union cvmx_bgxx_spux_fec_corr_blks01 {
07620     uint64_t u64;

07624                                                          * For 10GBASE-R, reserved.
07625                                                          * For 40GBASE-R, correspond to the Std 802.3 FEC_corrected_blocks_counter_1 variable
07626                                                          (registers 1.302-1.303). */
07627     uint64_t ln0_corr_blks                : 32; /**< PCS Lane 0 FEC corrected blocks.
07628                                                          * For 10GBASE-R, corresponds to the Std 802.3 FEC_corrected_blocks_counter variable
07629                                                          (registers 1.172-1.173).
07630                                                          * For 40GBASE-R, correspond to the Std 802.3 FEC_corrected_blocks_counter_0 variable
07631                                                          (registers 1.300-1.301). */
07632 #else

07634     uint64_t ln1_corr_blks                : 32;
07635 #endif
07636     } s;

07762     uint64_t training_failure             : 1;  /**< BASE-R PMD training failure. Set when BASE-R PMD link training has failed on the 10GBASE-R
07763                                                          lane or any 40GBASE-R lane. Valid if the LPCS type selected by
07764                                                          BGX()_CMR()_CONFIG[LMAC_TYPE] is 10GBASE-R or 40GBASE-R and
07765                                                          BGX()_SPU()_BR_PMD_CONTROL[TRAIN_EN] is 1, and never set otherwise. */
07766     uint64_t training_done                : 1;  /**< BASE-R PMD training done. Set when the 10GBASE-R lane or all 40GBASE-R lanes have
07767                                                          successfully completed BASE-R PMD link training. Valid if the LPCS type selected by

07769                                                          BGX()_SPU()_BR_PMD_CONTROL[TRAIN_EN] is 1, and never set otherwise. */
07770     uint64_t an_complete                  : 1;  /**< Autonegotiation complete. Set when BGX()_SPU()_AN_STATUS[AN_COMPLETE] is set,
07771                                                          indicating that the autonegotiation process has been completed and the link is up and
07772                                                          running using the negotiated highest common denominator (HCD) technology. */
07773     uint64_t an_link_good                 : 1;  /**< Autonegotiation link good. Set when the an_link_good variable is set as defined in
07774                                                          802.3-2008 Figure 73-11, indicating that autonegotiation has completed. */
07775     uint64_t an_page_rx                   : 1;  /**< Autonegotiation page received. This bit is set along with
07776                                                          BGX()_SPU()_AN_STATUS[PAGE_RX] when a new page has been received and stored in

07778     uint64_t fec_uncorr                   : 1;  /**< Uncorrectable FEC error. Set when an FEC block with an uncorrectable error is received on
07779                                                          the 10GBASE-R lane or any 40GBASE-R lane. Valid if the LPCS type selected by
07780                                                          BGX()_CMR()_CONFIG[LMAC_TYPE] is 10GBASE-R or 40GBASE-R, and never set otherwise. */
07781     uint64_t fec_corr                     : 1;  /**< Correctable FEC error. Set when an FEC block with a correctable error is received on the
07782                                                          10GBASE-R lane or any 40GBASE-R lane. Valid if the LPCS type selected by
07783                                                          BGX()_CMR()_CONFIG[LMAC_TYPE] is 10GBASE-R or 40GBASE-R, and never set otherwise. */
07784     uint64_t bip_err                      : 1;  /**< 40GBASE-R bit interleaved parity error. Set when a BIP error is detected on any lane.
07785                                                          Valid if the LPCS type selected by BGX()_CMR()_CONFIG[LMAC_TYPE] is 40GBASE-R, and
07786                                                          never set otherwise. */
07787     uint64_t dbg_sync                     : 1;  /**< Sync failure debug. This interrupt is provided for link problem debugging help. It is set
07788                                                          as follows based on the LPCS type selected by BGX()_CMR()_CONFIG[LMAC_TYPE], and
07789                                                          whether FEC is enabled or disabled by BGX()_SPU()_FEC_CONTROL[FEC_EN]:
07790                                                          * XAUI or RXAUI: Set when any lane's PCS synchronization state transitions from
07791                                                          SYNC_ACQUIRED_1 to SYNC_ACQUIRED_2 (see 802.3-2008 Figure 48-7).
07792                                                          * 10GBASE-R or 40GBASE-R with FEC disabled: Set when sh_invalid_cnt increments to 1 while
07793                                                          BLOCK_LOCK is 1 (see 802.3-2008 Figure 49-12 and 802.3ba-2010 Figure 82-20).
07794                                                          * 10GBASE-R or 40GBASE-R with FEC enabled: Set when parity_invalid_cnt increments to 1
07795                                                          while fec_block_lock is 1 (see 802.3-2008 Figure 74-8). */
07796     uint64_t algnlos                      : 1;  /**< Loss of lane alignment. Set when lane-to-lane alignment is lost. This is only valid if the
07797                                                          logical PCS is a multilane type (i.e. XAUI, RXAUI or 40GBASE-R is selected by
07798                                                          BGX()_CMR()_CONFIG[LMAC_TYPE]), and is never set otherwise. */
07799     uint64_t synlos                       : 1;  /**< Loss of lane sync. Lane code-group or block synchronization is lost on one or more lanes
07800                                                          associated with the LMAC/LPCS. Set as follows based on the LPCS type selected by
07801                                                          BGX()_CMR()_CONFIG[LMAC_TYPE], and whether FEC is enabled or disabled by
07802                                                          BGX()_SPU()_FEC_CONTROL[FEC_EN]:
07803                                                          * XAUI or RXAUI: Set when any lane's PCS synchronization state transitions to LOSS_OF_SYNC
07804                                                          (see 802.3-2008 Figure 48-7)
07805                                                          * 10GBASE-R or 40GBASE-R with FEC disabled: set when the BLOCK_LOCK variable is cleared on
07806                                                          the 10G lane or any 40G lane (see 802.3-2008 Figure 49-12 and 802.3ba-2010 Figure 82-20).
07807                                                          * 10GBASE-R or 40GBASE-R with FEC enabled: set when the fec_block_lock variable is cleared
07808                                                          on the 10G lane or any 40G lane (see 802.3-2008 Figure 74-8). */
07809     uint64_t bitlckls                     : 1;  /**< Bit lock lost on one or more lanes associated with the LMAC/LPCS. */
07810     uint64_t err_blk                      : 1;  /**< Errored block received. Set when an errored BASE-R block is received as described for
07811                                                          BGX()_SPU()_BR_STATUS2[ERR_BLKS]. Valid if the LPCS type selected by
07812                                                          BGX()_CMR()_CONFIG[LMAC_TYPE] is 10GBASE-R or 40GBASE-R, and never set otherwise. */
07813     uint64_t rx_link_down                 : 1;  /**< Set when the receive link goes down, which is the same condition that sets
07814                                                          BGX()_SPU()_STATUS2[RCVFLT]. */
07815     uint64_t rx_link_up                   : 1;  /**< Set when the receive link comes up, which is the same condition that allows the setting of
07816                                                          BGX()_SPU()_STATUS1[RCV_LNK]. */
07817 #else
07818     uint64_t rx_link_up                   : 1;
07819     uint64_t rx_link_down                 : 1;
07820     uint64_t err_blk                      : 1;
07821     uint64_t bitlckls                     : 1;
07822     uint64_t synlos                       : 1;
07823     uint64_t algnlos                      : 1;
07824     uint64_t dbg_sync                     : 1;
07825     uint64_t bip_err                      : 1;
07826     uint64_t fec_corr                     : 1;
07827     uint64_t fec_uncorr                   : 1;
07828     uint64_t an_page_rx                   : 1;
07829     uint64_t an_link_good                 : 1;
07830     uint64_t an_complete                  : 1;
07831     uint64_t training_done                : 1;
07832     uint64_t training_failure             : 1;
07833     uint64_t reserved_15_63               : 49;
07834 #endif
07835     } s;
07836     struct cvmx_bgxx_spux_int_s           cn73xx;
07837     struct cvmx_bgxx_spux_int_s           cn78xx;
07838     struct cvmx_bgxx_spux_int_s           cn78xxp1;
07839     struct cvmx_bgxx_spux_int_s           cnf75xx;

07874 /**
07875  * cvmx_bgx#_spu#_misc_control
07876  *
07877  * "* RX logical PCS lane polarity vector <3:0> = [XOR_RXPLRT]<3:0> ^ [4[[RXPLRT]]].
07878  *  * TX logical PCS lane polarity vector <3:0> = [XOR_TXPLRT]<3:0> ^ [4[[TXPLRT]]].
07879  *
07880  *  In short, keep [RXPLRT] and [TXPLRT] cleared, and use [XOR_RXPLRT] and [XOR_TXPLRT] fields to
07881  *  define
07882  *  the polarity per logical PCS lane. Only bit 0 of vector is used for 10GBASE-R, and only bits
07883  * - 1:0 of vector are used for RXAUI."
07884  */
07885 union cvmx_bgxx_spux_misc_control {
07886     uint64_t u64;
07887     struct cvmx_bgxx_spux_misc_control_s {
07888 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
07889     uint64_t reserved_13_63               : 51;
07890     uint64_t rx_packet_dis                : 1;  /**< Receive packet disable. Software can set or clear this bit at any time to gracefully
07891                                                          disable or re-enable packet reception by the LPCS. If this bit is set while a packet is
07892                                                          being received, the packet is completed and all subsequent received packets are discarded
07893                                                          by the LPCS. Similarly, if this bit is cleared while a received packet is being discarded,
07894                                                          packet reception resumes after the current packet is fully discarded. When set for a
07895                                                          40GBASE-R or 10GBASE-R LMAC/LPCS type (selected by BGX()_CMR()_CONFIG[LMAC_TYPE]),
07896                                                          received errors and faults will be ignored while receive packets are discarded; idles will
07897                                                          be sent to the MAC layer (SMU) and the errored blocks counter
07898                                                          (BGX()_SPU()_BR_STATUS2[ERR_BLKS]) will not increment. */
07899     uint64_t skip_after_term              : 1;  /**< Enable sending of idle skip after terminate. This bit is meaningful when the logical PCS
07900                                                          type is XAUI or RXAUI (selected by BGX()_CMR()_CONFIG[LMAC_TYPE]), and has no
07901                                                          effect otherwise. When set, the LMAC/LPCS transmits more idle skip columns for clock
07902                                                          compensation. Typically set in HiGig/HiGig2 modes; clear otherwise. This field can be set
07903                                                          to ensure sufficient density of XAUI idle skip (||R||) columns with a small transmit
07904                                                          inter-frame gap (IFG) in order to allow the link partner's receiver to delete ||R
07905                                                          columns as needed for clock rate compensation. It is usually set when the LMAC's transmit
07906                                                          IFG is set to 8 bytes in HiGig/HiGig2 modes (i.e. BGX()_SMU()_TX_IFG[IFG1] +
07907                                                          BGX()_SMU()_TX_IFG[IFG2] = 8), and should be cleared when the transmit IFG is
07908                                                          greater than 8 bytes. When this bit is set, the SPU will send an ||R|| column after a
07909                                                          ||T0|| column (terminate in lane 0) if no ||R|| was sent in the previous IFG. This is a
07910                                                          minor deviation from the functionality specified in 802.3-2008 Figure 48-6 (PCS transmit
07911                                                          source state diagram), whereby the state will transition directly from SEND_DATA to
07912                                                          SEND_RANDOM_R after ||T0|| if no ||R|| was transmitted in the previous IFG. Sending ||R
07913                                                          after ||T0|| only (and not ||T1||, |T2|| or ||T3||) ensures that the check_end function at
07914                                                          the receiving end, as defined in 802.3-2008 sub-clause 48.2.6.1.4, does not detect an
07915                                                          error due to this functional change. When this bit is clear, the LMAC will fully conform
07916                                                          to the functionality specified in Figure 48-6. */
07917     uint64_t intlv_rdisp                  : 1;  /**< RXAUI interleaved running disparity. This bit is meaningful when the logical PCS type is
07918                                                          RXAUI (BGX()_CMR()_CONFIG[LMAC_TYPE] = RXAUI), and has no effect otherwise. It
07919                                                          selects which disparity calculation to use when combining or splitting the RXAUI lanes, as
07920                                                          follows:
07921                                                          _ 0 = Common running disparity. Common running disparity is computed for even
07922                                                          and odd code-groups of an RXAUI lane, i.e. interleave lanes before PCS layer as
07923                                                          described in the Dune Networks/Broadcom RXAUI v2.1 specification. This obeys
07924                                                          6.25GHz SerDes disparity.
07925                                                          _ 1 = Interleaved running disparity: Running disparity is computed separately for even and
07926                                                          odd code-groups of an RXAUI lane, i.e. interleave lanes after PCS layer as described in
07927                                                          the Marvell RXAUI Interface specification. This does not obey 6.25GHz SerDes disparity. */
07928     uint64_t xor_rxplrt                   : 4;  /**< RX polarity control per logical PCS lane */
07929     uint64_t xor_txplrt                   : 4;  /**< TX polarity control per logical PCS lane */
07930     uint64_t rxplrt                       : 1;  /**< Receive polarity. 1 = inverted polarity, 0 = normal polarity. */
07931     uint64_t txplrt                       : 1;  /**< Transmit polarity. 1 = inverted polarity, 0 = normal polarity. */
07932 #else
07933     uint64_t txplrt                       : 1;
07934     uint64_t rxplrt                       : 1;
07935     uint64_t xor_txplrt                   : 4;
07936     uint64_t xor_rxplrt                   : 4;
07937     uint64_t intlv_rdisp                  : 1;
07938     uint64_t skip_after_term              : 1;
07939     uint64_t rx_packet_dis                : 1;
07940     uint64_t reserved_13_63               : 51;
07941 #endif
07942     } s;
07943     struct cvmx_bgxx_spux_misc_control_s  cn73xx;
07944     struct cvmx_bgxx_spux_misc_control_s  cn78xx;
07945     struct cvmx_bgxx_spux_misc_control_s  cn78xxp1;
07946     struct cvmx_bgxx_spux_misc_control_s  cnf75xx;
07947 };
07948 typedef union cvmx_bgxx_spux_misc_control cvmx_bgxx_spux_misc_control_t;

08087 /**
08088  * cvmx_bgx#_spu_dbg_control
08089  */
08090 union cvmx_bgxx_spu_dbg_control {
08091     uint64_t u64;
08092     struct cvmx_bgxx_spu_dbg_control_s {
08093 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
08094     uint64_t reserved_56_63               : 8;
08095     uint64_t ms_clk_period                : 12; /**< Millisecond clock period. Specifies the number of microsecond clock ticks per millisecond,
08096                                                          minus 1. The default value of 999 (0x3E7) should be used during normal operation; other
08097                                                          values may be used for test/debug purposes. */
08098     uint64_t us_clk_period                : 12; /**< Microsecond clock period. Specifies the number of SCLK cycles per microseconds, minus 1.
08099                                                          For example, if SCLK runs at 1.3 GHz, the number of SCLK cycles per microsecond is 1,300
08100                                                          so the value of this field should be 1,299 (0x513). This is used by the BASE-R BER monitor
08101                                                          timers. */
08102     uint64_t reserved_31_31               : 1;
08103     uint64_t br_ber_mon_dis               : 1;  /**< BASE-R bit error rate monitor disable. This bit should be clear for normal operation.
08104                                                          Setting it disables the BASE-R BER monitor state machine defined in 802.3-2008 Figure
08105                                                          49-13 for 10GBASE-R and 802.3ba-2010 Figure 82-13 for 40GBASE-R. */
08106     uint64_t an_nonce_match_dis           : 1;  /**< Autonegotiation nonce match disable. This bit should be clear for normal operation.
08107                                                          Setting it disables Nonce Match check by forcing nonce_match variable to 0 in the
08108                                                          autonegotiation arbitration state diagram, as defined in 802.3-2008 Figure 73-11. This bit
08109                                                          can
08110                                                          be set by software for test purposes, e.g. for running autonegotiation in loopback mode. */
08111     uint64_t timestamp_norm_dis           : 1;  /**< 40GBASE-R RX timestamp normalization disable. This bit controls the generation of the
08112                                                          receive SOP timestamp passed to the SMU sub-block for a 40GBASE-R LMAC/LPCS. When this bit
08113                                                          is clear, SPU normalizes the receive SOP timestamp in order to compensate for lane-to-lane
08114                                                          skew on a 40GBASE-R link, as described below. When this bit is set, timestamp
08115                                                          normalization is disabled and SPU directly passes the captured SOP timestamp values to
08116                                                          SMU.
08117                                                          In 40GBASE-R mode, a packet's SOP block can be transferred on any of the LMAC's lanes. In
08118                                                          the presence of lane-to-lane skew, the SOP delay from transmit (by the link partner) to
08119                                                          receive by SPU varies depending on which lane is used by the SOP block. This variation
08120                                                          reduces the accuracy of the received SOP timestamp relative to when it was transmitted by
08121                                                          the link partner.
08122                                                          SPU captures the timestamp of the alignment marker received on each SerDes lane during
08123                                                          align/skew detection; the captured value can be read from the SerDes lane's
08124                                                          BGX()_SPU_SDS()_SKEW_STATUS[SKEW_STATUS] field (BGX_SPU_SDS_SKEW_STATUS_S[AM_TIMESTAMP]
08125                                                          sub-field). If
08126                                                          alignment markers are transmitted at about the same time on all lanes by the link partner,
08127                                                          then the difference between the BGX_SPU_SDS_SKEW_STATUS_S[AM_TIMESTAMP] values for a pair
08128                                                          of lanes represents the
08129                                                          approximate skew between those lanes.
08130                                                          SPU uses the 40GBASE-R LMAC's programmed PCS lane 0 as a reference and computes the
08131                                                          BGX_SPU_SDS_SKEW_STATUS_S[AM_TIMESTAMP] delta of every other lane relative to PCS lane 0.
08132                                                          When normalization is
08133                                                          enabled, SPU adjusts the timestamp of a received SOP by subtracting the receiving lane's
08134                                                          BGX_SPU_SDS_SKEW_STATUS_S[AM_TIMESTAMP] delta from the captured timestamp value. The
08135                                                          adjusted/normalized timestamp
08136                                                          value is then passed to SMU along with the SOP.
08137                                                          Software can determine the actual maximum skew of a 40GBASE-R link by examining the
08138                                                          BGX_SPU_SDS_SKEW_STATUS_S[AM_TIMESTAMP] values in the BGX()_SPU_SDS()_SKEW_STATUS
08139                                                          registers, and decide if
08140                                                          timestamp normalization should be enabled or disabled to improve PTP accuracy.
08141                                                          Normalization improves accuracy for larger skew values but reduces the accuracy (due to
08142                                                          timestamp measurement errors) for small skew values. */
08143     uint64_t rx_buf_flip_synd             : 8;  /**< Flip SPU receive buffer FIFO ECC bits. Two bits per SerDes lane; used to inject single-bit
08144                                                          and
08145                                                          double-bit errors into the ECC field on writes to the associated SPU receive buffer lane
08146                                                          FIFO, as
08147                                                          follows:
08148                                                          0x0 = Normal operation.
08149                                                          0x1 = SBE on ECC bit 0.
08150                                                          0x2 = SBE on ECC bit 1.
08151                                                          0x3 = DBE on ECC bits 1:0. */
08152     uint64_t br_pmd_train_soft_en         : 1;  /**< Enable BASE-R PMD software controlled link training. This bit configures the operation
08153                                                          mode for BASE-R link training for all LMACs and lanes. When this bit is set along with
08154                                                          BGX()_SPU()_BR_PMD_CONTROL[TRAIN_EN] for a given LMAC, the BASE-R link training
08155                                                          protocol for that LMAC is executed under software control, whereby the contents the
08156                                                          BGX()_SPU()_BR_PMD_LD_CUP and BGX()_SPU()_BR_PMD_LD_REP registers are
08157                                                          updated by software. When this bit is clear and
08158                                                          BGX()_SPU()_BR_PMD_CONTROL[TRAIN_EN] is set, the link training protocol is fully
08159                                                          automated in hardware, whereby the contents BGX()_SPU()_BR_PMD_LD_CUP and
08160                                                          BGX()_SPU()_BR_PMD_LD_REP registers are automatically updated by hardware. */
08161     uint64_t an_arb_link_chk_en           : 1;  /**< Enable link status checking by autonegotiation arbitration state machine. When
08162                                                          autonegotiation is enabled (BGX()_SPU()_AN_CONTROL[AN_EN] is set), this bit controls
08163                                                          the behavior of the autonegotiation arbitration state machine when it reaches the AN GOOD
08164                                                          CHECK state after DME pages are successfully exchanged, as defined in Figure 73-11 in
08165                                                          802.3-2008.
08166                                                          When this bit is set and the negotiated highest common denominator (HCD) technology
08167                                                          matches BGX()_CMR()_CONFIG[LMAC_TYPE], the autonegotiation arbitration SM
08168                                                          performs the actions defined for the AN GOOD CHECK state in Figure 73-11, i.e. run the
08169                                                          link_fail_inhibit timer and eventually transition to the AN GOOD or TRANSMIT DISABLE
08170                                                          state.
08171                                                          When this bit is clear or the HCD technology does not match BGX()_CMR()_CONFIG[LMAC_TYPE],
08172                                                          the AN arbitration
08173                                                          SM stays in the AN GOOD CHECK state, with the expectation that software will perform the
08174                                                          appropriate actions to complete the autonegotiation protocol, as follows:
08175                                                          * If this bit is clear and the HCD technology matches BGX()_CMR()_CONFIG[LMAC_TYPE], clear
08176                                                          BGX()_SPU()_AN_CONTROL[AN_EN].
08177                                                          * Otherwise, disable the LPCS by clearing the BGX()_CMR()_CONFIG[ENABLE], clear
08178                                                          BGX()_SPU()_AN_CONTROL[AN_EN], reconfigure the LPCS with the correct
08179                                                          BGX()_CMR()_CONFIG[LMAC_TYPE],
08180                                                          and re-enable the LPCS by setting BGX()_CMR()_CONFIG[ENABLE].
08181                                                          In both cases, software should implement the link_fail_inhibit timer and verify the link
08182                                                          status as specified for the AN GOOD CHECK state. */
08183     uint64_t rx_buf_cor_dis               : 1;  /**< When set, disables ECC correction on all SPU receive buffer FIFOs. */
08184     uint64_t scramble_dis                 : 1;  /**< BASE-R scrambler/descrambler disable. Setting this bit to 1 disables the BASE-R scrambler
08185                                                          & descrambler functions and FEC PN-2112 scrambler & descrambler functions for debug
08186                                                          purposes. */
08187     uint64_t reserved_15_15               : 1;
08188     uint64_t marker_rxp                   : 15; /**< BASE-R alignment marker receive period. For a multilane BASE-R logical PCS (i.e.
08189                                                          40GBASE-R), this field specifies the expected alignment marker receive period per lane,
08190                                                          i.e. the expected number of received 66b non-marker blocks between consecutive markers on
08191                                                          the same lane. The default value corresponds to a period of 16363 blocks (exclusive) as
08192                                                          specified in 802.3ba-2010. Must be greater than 64. */
08193 #else
08194     uint64_t marker_rxp                   : 15;
08195     uint64_t reserved_15_15               : 1;
08196     uint64_t scramble_dis                 : 1;
08197     uint64_t rx_buf_cor_dis               : 1;
08198     uint64_t an_arb_link_chk_en           : 1;
08199     uint64_t br_pmd_train_soft_en         : 1;
08200     uint64_t rx_buf_flip_synd             : 8;
08201     uint64_t timestamp_norm_dis           : 1;
08202     uint64_t an_nonce_match_dis           : 1;
08203     uint64_t br_ber_mon_dis               : 1;
08204     uint64_t reserved_31_31               : 1;
08205     uint64_t us_clk_period                : 12;
08206     uint64_t ms_clk_period                : 12;
08207     uint64_t reserved_56_63               : 8;
08208 #endif
08209     } s;
